Introduction
In real-world API testing, you often need to:

Send dynamic data instead of hardcoded values
Test with multiple data sets (parameterization)
Load payloads from external files (JSON, Excel)
Upload files (screenshots, PDFs) via API
Authenticate using OAuth 2.0
This guide covers these advanced strategies using REST Assured and TestNG.

Dynamic JSON Payload Construction
The Problem with Hardcoded Payloads
// Hardcoded - will always create the same book
String body = "{\"name\":\"Learn Appium\",\"isbn\":\"bcd\",\"aisle\":\"227\"}";
Running the test twice will fail because the book already exists
Cannot test different data sets without code changes
Solution: Build Payload Dynamically Using Variables
Step 1: Create a method that accepts parameters

public static String Addbook(String isbn, String aisle) {
    return "{\n" +
            "\"name\":\"Learn Appium Automation with Java\",\n" +
            "\"isbn\":\"" + isbn + "\",\n" +
            "\"aisle\":\"" + aisle + "\",\n" +
            "\"author\":\"John foe\"\n" +
            "}";
}
Step 2: Use string concatenation correctly

// Pattern for inserting variables into JSON strings:
// "prefix" + variable + "suffix"
"\"isbn\":\"" + isbn + "\","
//         ↑       ↑     ↑
//      close    var   open
//      string         string
Step 3: Call from test

java

@Test
public void addBook() {
    Response resp = given()
        .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
        .body(payLoad.Addbook("ABC123", "4567"))  // dynamic values
        .post("/Library/Addbook.php");
}
Best Practice: Always delete the resource after testing (cleanup) to maintain test idempotency.

Parameterizing Tests with Multiple Data Sets
TestNG DataProvider Annotation
Use @DataProvider to run the same test with multiple data sets.

@DataProvider(name = "BooksData")
public Object[][] getData() {
    return new Object[][] {
        {"isbn1", "aisle1"},
        {"isbn2", "aisle2"},
        {"isbn3", "aisle3"}
    };
}
How It Works:

Each inner array represents one test iteration
Test method receives parameters in the same order
Test runs once for each array
Complete Example
import org.testng.annotations.DataProvider;
import org.testng.annotations.Test;
import static io.restassured.RestAssured.*;
public class DynamicJsonTest {
    @Test(dataProvider = "BooksData")
    public void addBook(String isbn, String aisle) {
        baseURI = "http://216.10.245.166";
        
        Response resp = given()
            .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
            .body(payLoad.Addbook(isbn, aisle))
            .post("/Library/Addbook.php")
            .then().assertThat().statusCode(200)
            .extract().response();
        
        String id = JsonPath.from(resp.asString()).getString("ID");
        System.out.println("Created Book ID: " + id);
    }
    @DataProvider(name = "BooksData")
    public Object[][] getData() {
        return new Object[][] {
            {"ojfwty", "9363"},
            {"cwetee", "4253"},
            {"okmfet", "533"}
        };
    }
}
Important Rules:

RuleExplanationSame number of argumentsTest method parameters must match array elements countSame data typesParameter types must match the data types in arrayReturn type Object[][]DataProvider must return 2D Object arrayName matching@Test(dataProvider="name") must match @DataProvider(name="name")

