Using External JSON Files as Payload
Why Use External Files?
Developers may share JSON files for testing
Keeps test code clean
Useful for static payloads that don’t change
Implementation
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Paths;
public class StaticJsonTest {
    
    @Test
    public void addBook() throws IOException {
        baseURI = "http://216.10.245.166";
        
        Response resp = given()
            .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
            .body(GenerateStringFromResource("C:\\path\\to\\Addbookdetails.json"))
            .post("/Library/Addbook.php");
    }
    
    public static String GenerateStringFromResource(String path) throws IOException {
        // Read all bytes from file, convert to String
        return new String(Files.readAllBytes(Paths.get(path)));
    }
}
Step-by-Step Breakdown:
Files.readAllBytes(Paths.get(path)) → reads file as byte array
new String(byteArray) → converts bytes to String
Pass the String to .body()
Note: This approach works only for static payloads. For dynamic values, use the concatenation or DataProvider methods.

