Postman API Testing Automation - Complete Study Notes Part 2 draft1
This resource consolidates all concepts covered in the lectures into a structured, self-contained guide. Every topic is explained with practical examples, best practices, and a quick-revision cheat sheet. No external files or transcripts are needed.
1. Introduction to API Testing with Postman

Postman is a versatile tool for manual and automated testing of REST APIs.
Automation ensures:
Correct HTTP status codes (200, 404, etc.)
Proper JSON response structure
Functional correctness (CRUD operations)
Performance (response time)
Data integrity when chaining multiple requests
Tests are written in JavaScript using Postman's built-in sandbox.
A Collection groups related requests; a Runner executes them sequentially.
Integration with Newman and Jenkins enables CI/CD execution and HTML reporting.

---

2. Environments and Variables
2.1 The Role of Environments
An environment is a named set of key‑value pairs (variables) that can be switched instantly.
Instead of hard‑coding server URLs, you store them in variables and select the appropriate environment before running tests.
Typical environments: QA, UAT, Production.

Example:
QA environment: baseUrl = https://qa.example.com
UAT environment: baseUrl = https://uat.example.com

2.2 Creating an Environment

Go to the Environments tab.
Click + and give it a name (e.g., "UAT").
Add variables like baseUrl and their values.
In recent Postman versions, there is a single Value field; earlier versions had separate INITIAL VALUE and CURRENT VALUE. Always fill the Value field.

2.3 Variable Scopes and Precedence
Variables can be created at different levels. If the same variable name exists in multiple scopes, the narrowest scope wins.
Scopes (from narrowest to broadest):
Local - Defined in a Pre‑request or Test script (pm.variables.set()); available only within that request.
Data - Comes from external CSV/JSON files during a Runner iteration.
Environment - Defined inside an environment; available only when that environment is selected.
Collection - Defined in the collection's Variables tab; available to all requests within that collection.
Global - Defined in the Globals pane (footer); available across the entire workspace.

Best practice:
Use Global for truly universal constants (company code, API version).
Use Environment for server‑specific data (base URL, tokens).
Use Collection for data shared among requests in a specific test suite (IDs, generated values).
Avoid Local unless absolutely necessary.

2.4 Using Variables in Requests

Enclose variable names in double curly braces: {{variableName}}.
Example: GET {{baseUrl}}/books/{{bookId}}.
At runtime, Postman replaces the placeholder with the actual value from the active scope.

2.5 Dynamic Environment Switching

Without variables, changing a server URL requires editing every request manually.
With variables, just select a different environment from the dropdown; all requests immediately use the new base URL.
This is essential when the same collection must be run on multiple servers (QA → UAT → Prod).

---

3. Pre‑request Scripts and Dynamic Data Generation
Pre‑request scripts run before a request is sent. They are used to set up dynamic data, generate unique values, or manipulate variables.
3.1 Accessing Variables in Scripts

Global: pm.globals.get("varName") / pm.globals.set("varName", value)
Environment: pm.environment.get("varName") / pm.environment.set("varName", value)
Collection: pm.collectionVariables.get("varName") / pm.collectionVariables.set("varName", value)

3.2 Using Built‑in Dynamic Variables

Postman provides many placeholder values that are replaced at runtime. Common ones:
{{$randomInt}} – random integer between 0 and 1000

{{$timestamp}} – current Unix timestamp

{{$guid}} – globally unique identifier

{{$randomAlphaNumeric}} – random string

To use them inside a script:
javascript
let randomValue = pm.variables.replaceIn('{{$randomInt}}');

3.3 Example: Generating a Unique ISBN

Requirement: Every book must have a unique ISBN. The company standard is RS followed by a random number.
Step‑by‑step implementation:
Define company code as a global variable

In Globals, add companyCode = "RS".

This value is constant across all environments and collections.

Pre‑request script of the "Add Book" request
javascript

// Retrieve the company code let code = pm.globals.get("companyCode"); // Generate a random integer let randomVal = pm.variables.replaceIn('{{$randomInt}}'); // Construct the ISBN let isbn = code + randomVal; // Store it in a collection variable so the request body can use it pm.collectionVariables.set("isbn", isbn);

Request body (JSON)
json

{ "book_name": "Learn Postman", "isbn": "{{isbn}}", "author": "John Doe" }

Because the pre‑request script runs first, {{isbn}} is already populated with a fresh value before the request is sent.

Why this matters:
Without dynamic ISBNs, repeated runs would fail with "book already exists".

Each execution creates a new book, making the test repeatable and reliable.

---

4. Writing Tests and Assertions

Tests are written in the Tests tab and execute after the response arrives. Each test block contains one or more assertions.
4.1 Basic Test Structure

javascript
pm.test("Test name", function () {
    // Assertions
});

If any assertion fails, that test is marked as failed.
4.2 Common Assertions and Examples

4.2.1 Status Code

javascript
pm.test("Status code is 200", function () {
    pm.response.to.have.status(200);
});

4.2.2 Response Body (JSON Fields)

First, parse the response:
javascript
let jsonData = pm.response.json();

Then assert:
javascript
pm.test("Message equals 'success'", function () {
    pm.expect(jsonData.message).to.equal("success");
});

When the response is an array (e.g., [ { … } ]), index into it:
javascript
pm.test("Author is correct", function () {
    pm.expect(jsonData[0].author).to.equal("Expected Author");
});

4.2.3 Response Headers

Check header existence:

javascript
pm.test("Content-Type header is present", function () {
    pm.response.to.have.header("Content-Type");
});

Validate header value:

javascript
pm.test("Content-Type is application/json", function () {
    pm.expect(pm.response.headers.get("Content-Type")).to.equal("application/json; charset=utf-8");
});

4.2.4 Response Time

javascript
pm.test("Response time is under 1200ms", function () {
    pm.expect(pm.response.responseTime).to.be.below(1200);
});

This ensures performance thresholds are met.
4.2.5 Substring Presence (Text Contains)

Use when you only care that a certain text appears anywhere in the response.
javascript
pm.test("Response contains 'success'", function () {
    pm.expect(pm.response.text()).to.include("success");
});

pm.response.text() returns the entire response body as a string.
4.3 How to Discover the Correct Syntax

Postman's JavaScript reference documentation is built into the tool.

You can inspect the response object by printing it to the Postman Console: console.log(pm.response)

The documentation clearly shows which properties are available (e.g., pm.response.json(), pm.response.headers, pm.response.responseTime).

---

5. Extracting Data and Chaining Requests (CRUD Flow)

5.1 The Problem

When you add a book, the server returns an ID. That ID must be used in subsequent GET and DELETE requests. Manually copying the ID is not automation.
5.2 Solution: Use Variables to Share Data Between Requests

In the "Add Book" request's Tests tab:
Extract the ID from the response.

Store it in a variable (environment or collection).

javascript
let jsonData = pm.response.json();
let bookId = jsonData.id;               // assuming the response contains "id"
pm.environment.set("bookId", bookId);   // or pm.collectionVariables.set

In the "Get Book" request:
Set a query parameter like ID = {{bookId}}.

In the "Delete Book" request:
Use {{bookId}} in the URL or request body.

5.3 Execution Order in the Collection Runner

When the whole collection is run, Postman executes requests sequentially as arranged. The "Add Book" test stores the ID, and the next requests retrieve it automatically. All assertions in each request are evaluated.
Important: Always click Save after editing any request; otherwise, changes may not be picked up during the run.

---

6. JSON Schema Validation

Schema validation confirms that the response structure matches the expected contract (data types, required fields, array vs object). It is a critical layer of defence before UI testing.
6.1 Generating a JSON Schema

Send a request and copy a sample response.

Use an online JSON Schema generator (e.g., search "JSON Schema Generator").

Paste the sample JSON; the tool produces a schema object.

Example schema snippet (for a book response that is an array):
json
{
    "type": "array",
    "items": {
        "type": "object",
        "required": ["book_name", "isbn", "author"],
        "properties": {
            "book_name": {"type": "string"},
            "isbn": {"type": "string"},
            "author": {"type": "string"}
        }
    }
}

6.2 Writing the Schema Validation Test

javascript
const expectedSchema = { /* paste generated schema */ };
pm.test("Response schema is valid", function () {
    pm.response.to.have.jsonSchema(expectedSchema);
});

If a required field is missing, or a data type differs (e.g., isbn appears as an integer instead of a string), the test fails.

This catches backend changes that could break the consumer (frontend or other services).

---

7. Data‑Driven Testing (Concept)

Postman's Collection Runner can use external data files (CSV or JSON) to run the same requests with multiple input sets.

Variables like {{bookName}} and {{isbn}} are defined in the data file; the runner iterates over each row.

This is ideal for bulk operations, e.g., uploading 100 books from an Excel sheet.

---

8. CI/CD Integration with Newman

Newman is Postman's command‑line collection runner.

It can execute collections and output results in CLI, JSON, HTML, etc.

Typical usage:
text

newman run myCollection.json -e myEnvironment.json - reporters cli,html

Integrate with Jenkins (or any CI tool) by adding a build step that runs Newman.

Publish the HTML report for immediate visibility into test results.

---

9. Collaboration and Version Control

Postman supports team workspaces where multiple users can collaborate on collections.

Changes can be tracked using Postman's built‑in version control (forking, merging, pull requests).

Collections and environments can also be exported as JSON files and stored in Git repositories.

Resolve merge conflicts directly within Postman when multiple people modify the same collection.

---

10. Best Practices Summary

Never hard‑code URLs or sensitive data - always use variables.

Environment variables - server‑specific data (base URL, tokens).

Collection variables - test‑flow data (bookId, dynamic ISBN).

Global variables - truly constant values across all environments (company code).

Pre‑request scripts - generate dynamic data before each request.

Tests tab - always validate status codes, response time, schema, and critical data.

Chain requests - mimic real‑user flows by passing data between requests.

Handle "already exists" scenarios - generate unique data or use smart teardown/cleanup logic.

Use the Collection Runner to confirm end‑to‑end functionality.

Integrate with CI/CD for continuous regression testing.

---

11. Typical Interview Questions and Answers

How do you pass data between requests in Postman?
Extract the value from the response using pm.response.json() and store it in an environment or collection variable. Use {{variableName}} in subsequent requests.

What is the difference between environment and global variables?
Environment variables change when you switch environments; global variables are always available regardless of the selected environment.

How do you validate a JSON schema?
Generate a schema from a sample response using an online tool. In the Tests tab, call pm.response.to.have.jsonSchema(expectedSchema).

When would you use a pre‑request script?
To prepare dynamic data (e.g., unique ISBN, timestamp) or set up variables before the request is sent.

Explain variable precedence.
If the same variable name exists in multiple scopes, Postman uses the value from the narrowest scope: Local → Data → Environment → Collection → Global.

How do you run collections from the command line?
Using Newman: newman run collection.json -e environment.json. It can be integrated into Jenkins or other CI tools.

How do you handle a "book already exists" error in automated tests?
By generating a unique ISBN each time (dynamic data) or by adding a teardown step that deletes the book before adding it again.

