Comprehensive OAuth 2.0 Notes - Authorization Code Grant Flow - Draft Postman

Introduction to OAuth 2.0

What is OAuth 2.0?
An open standard protocol for authorization (not authentication)

Allows third-party applications to access user data without exposing passwords

Provides delegated access to resources

Most widely used authorization framework on the internet today

Why OAuth 2.0 is Important
99.99% of enterprise APIs use OAuth 2.0, primarily Authorization Code or Client Credentials grant types

Eliminates the need to store user credentials on your servers

Reduces security risks and data breach liabilities

Enables single sign-on (SSO) across multiple applications

Key Problem OAuth Solves
Instead of giving your passwords to every application (BookMyShow, Uber, etc.), OAuth allows these apps to request permission from Google/Facebook to access only specific information (name, email) without ever seeing your password.

---

Core OAuth 2.0 Terminology

Resource Owner
The end user who owns the data (e.g., you with your Google account)

Grants permission to applications to access their protected resources

Client
The application requesting access to resources (e.g., BookMyShow, Uber, your application)

Needs to be registered with the authorization server

Authorization Server
Issues access tokens after successfully authenticating the resource owner

Examples: Google's accounts.google.com, Facebook's authorization endpoint

Resource Server
Hosts the protected user data (e.g., Google's user profile database)

Validates access tokens before serving requests

Client ID
Public identifier for the client application

Generated when you register your application with the authorization server

Not a secret; can be exposed in URLs and browser console

Client Secret
Confidential password-like credential for the client

Must be kept secure, never exposed in client-side code

Used to authenticate the client to the authorization server

Scope
Defines the specific level of access being requested

Example: https://www.googleapis.com/auth/userinfo.email requests only email access

Users see exactly what permissions they are granting

Authorization Code
Short-lived, one-time use code (like an OTP)

Returned by the authorization server after user authentication

Exchanged for an access token

Access Token
Credential used to access protected resources

Has an expiration time (typically 1–2 hours)

Sent with each API request (usually in Authorization header)

Redirect URI / Callback URL
Where the authorization server sends the user after authentication

Must exactly match what was registered with the authorization server

State Parameter
Optional security parameter to prevent CSRF attacks

Client sends a random string and validates the same string is returned

---

Authorization Code Grant Flow - Complete Walkthrough

Step-by-Step Flow Diagram

text
User -> Client App -> Authorization Server -> User Login -> Authorization Code -> Client App -> Token Endpoint -> Access Token -> Resource Server -> Protected Data

Detailed Steps

Step 1: User Initiates Login
User clicks "Login with Google" on client application (e.g., BookMyShow)

Application prepares authorization request URL

Step 2: Redirect to Authorization Server
Browser redirects to Google's authorization endpoint

URL contains: client_id, redirect_uri, response_type=code, scope, state

Step 3: User Authenticates
User enters Google credentials directly on Google's page

Password never shared with the client application

User sees scope permissions being requested

Step 4: Authorization Code Returned
Upon successful authentication, Google redirects back to redirect_uri

Authorization code appended as query parameter: ?code=4/0AY0e-g6...

State parameter (if used) returned for validation

Step 5: Client Exchanges Code for Token
Client makes POST request to token endpoint

Sends: code, client_id, client_secret, redirect_uri, grant_type=authorization_code

This is a back-channel call (server-to-server, no browser involvement)

Step 6: Access Token Received
Authorization server validates code and client credentials

Returns access_token (and optionally refresh_token, id_token)

Client stores this token

Step 7: Access Protected Resources
Client includes access_token in API requests

Resource server validates token before returning data

Token sent in Authorization header: Bearer ya29.a0AfH6...

---

Real-World Example - BookMyShow with Google Login

Scenario: User wants to book movie tickets using their Google account
Why BookMyShow uses OAuth 2.0:
No need to store passwords (reduces security liability)

No need to manage user registration/forgot password flows

Google handles all authentication complexity

Receives verified user information (name, email) automatically

Can send booking confirmations to user's Gmail

What Google shares:
First name, last name, email address, profile picture

Password is NEVER shared with BookMyShow

What happens when you "Login with Google":
BookMyShow redirects to Google's authorization server

You authenticate with Google (entering password on Google's domain)

Google asks: "BookMyShow wants access to your name and email. Allow?"

Upon approval, Google redirects back to BookMyShow with authorization code

BookMyShow exchanges code for access token (server-to-server)

BookMyShow uses token to fetch your profile from Google's resource server

You are now logged in to BookMyShow

---

API Endpoints and Parameters

Authorization Request (Get Code)

Endpoint: Authorization Server URL
Method: GET
Required Query Parameters:
scope - What data you need (e.g., https://www.googleapis.com/auth/userinfo.email)

client_id - Your application's public identifier

response_type - Must be code for authorization code flow

redirect_uri - Where to send the authorization code after login

Optional Query Parameters:
state - Random string for CSRF protection (highly recommended)

auth_url - Not standard; some implementations include this

access_type - offline to get refresh token

Example Authorization URL:
text
https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/v2/auth?
scope=https://www.googleapis.com/auth/userinfo.email&
client_id=692183103107-p0m7ent2hk7suguv4vq22hjcfhcr43pj.apps.googleusercontent.com&
response_type=code&
redirect_uri=https://rahulshettyacademy.com/getCourse.php

Token Exchange Request (Get Access Token)

Endpoint: Access Token URL
Method: POST
Required Parameters:
code - The authorization code received from Step 1

client_id - Your application's public identifier

client_secret - Your application's confidential secret

redirect_uri - Must match the one used in authorization request

grant_type - Must be authorization_code

Example Token Request:
text
POST https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v4/token?
code=4/0AY0e-g6UUD1-sMKIpsxzb520ZVflKe7i8xD_oQk6X3t_fjDqhaROnrJncgGX7dEF0jllVg&
client_id=692183103107-p0m7ent2hk7suguv4vq22hjcfhcr43pj.apps.googleusercontent.com&
client_secret=erZOWM9g3UtwNRj340YYaK_W&
redirect_uri=https://rahulshettyacademy.com/getCourse.php&
grant_type=authorization_code

Typical Token Response:
json
{
  "access_token": "ya29.a0AfH6SMD-EytFH41srRFqd55ewFQGIJD...",
  "expires_in": 3600,
  "refresh_token": "1//0geXXhYq0FvXRCgYIARAAGBASNwF...",
  "scope": "https://www.googleapis.com/auth/userinfo.email",
  "token_type": "Bearer"
}

Actual API Request (Using Access Token)

Method: GET, POST, etc.
Authorization: Access token can be sent as:
Query parameter: ?access_token=ya29...

HTTP Header: Authorization: Bearer ya29... (preferred)

Example:
text
GET https://rahulshettyacademy.com/getCourse.php?access_token=ya29.a0AfH6SMD...

---

Postman Implementation Steps

Step 1: Get Authorization Code
Open authorization URL in browser (not in Postman directly)

Log in with credentials

Copy the code parameter from redirect URL

Code appears after ?code= in browser address bar

Step 2: Exchange Code for Access Token in Postman
Create POST request to token endpoint

Add all required parameters as query parameters or form data

Send request

Copy access_token from response

Step 3: Access Protected Resource
Create GET request to actual API endpoint

Add access_token as query parameter or Authorization header

Send request to get protected data

Important Note: Step 1 (user login) cannot be automated in Postman because it requires browser-based user interaction. You must manually get the code from browser.

---

OAuth 2.0 Grant Types

Authorization Code Grant (Most Common - 50% of use cases)
Used by web applications with server-side backend

Most secure as tokens never exposed to browser

Enables refresh tokens for long-term access

Client Credentials Grant (Second Most Common - 40% of use cases)
Server-to-server communication (no user involved)

Application acts on its own behalf, not a user's

Used for machine-to-machine API calls

Implicit Grant (Deprecated/Obsolute)
Previously for single-page applications

No authorization code exchange

Not recommended anymore due to security concerns

Resource Owner Password Credentials Grant
User gives username/password directly to client

Only for trusted first-party applications

Rarely used due to security implications

Refresh Token Grant
Used to obtain new access tokens after expiration

Requires refresh_token from initial authorization

Prevents users from needing to re-authenticate frequently

---

Best Practices

Security Best Practices:
Always use HTTPS for all OAuth endpoints

Never expose client_secret in client-side code (browser/mobile apps)

Validate state parameter to prevent CSRF attacks

Keep access tokens confidential and transmit only over secure channels

Implement proper token storage (never store in localStorage for web apps)

Use short-lived access tokens (typically 1 hour or less)

Implement refresh token rotation for better security

Development Best Practices:
Always request minimal scopes (least privilege principle)

Register separate clients for development, staging, and production

Use environment variables for client_secret (never hardcode)

Implement proper error handling for token expiration

Log OAuth failures for debugging (without exposing secrets)

Testing Best Practices:
Get all required details from development team (client_id, client_secret, endpoints)

Create mock OAuth servers for integration testing

Test token expiration and refresh scenarios

Validate error responses (invalid_grant, invalid_client, etc.)

---

Common OAuth 2.0 Interview Questions

Q1: What is the difference between authentication and authorization?
Authentication verifies WHO you are (login with password)

Authorization determines WHAT you can do (permissions to access resources)

OAuth 2.0 handles authorization, not authentication

Q2: Why use Authorization Code grant over Implicit grant?
Authorization code flow exchanges code for token on back-channel

Access token never exposed in browser redirects

Critical for security in production applications

Enables refresh tokens for long-lived access

Q3: What is the purpose of the state parameter?
Prevents Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks

Client generates random value and validates returned value matches

Ensures the response corresponds to the actual request made

Q4: How do you handle expired access tokens?
Use refresh_token to get new access token without user interaction

Refresh token also expires eventually (typically longer-lived)

Implement token refresh logic before API calls or on 401 responses

Q5: What information does OAuth 2.0 provide about the user?
OAuth 2.0 itself provides no user info (just tokens)

Use access token to call UserInfo endpoint

OpenID Connect extends OAuth 2.0 for authentication and user identity

Q6: Can you automate the entire OAuth 2.0 flow in Postman?
Step 1 (authorization code) requires manual browser interaction

User must physically log in to authorization server

Step 2 and 3 can be automated in Postman

Some OAuth flows (Client Credentials) can be fully automated

Q7: What are common OAuth 2.0 endpoints?
Authorization Endpoint: Where user logs in and grants permission

Token Endpoint: Where code is exchanged for tokens

Redirection Endpoint: Where user returns after authorization

(Optional) UserInfo Endpoint: Where user profile is fetched

Q8: Why is client_secret required in token exchange but not in authorization request?
Authorization request is browser-based (public)

Token exchange is server-to-server (private)

client_secret must never be exposed in browser

---

Additional Important Concepts

PKCE (Proof Key for Code Exchange)
Extension for public clients (mobile/native apps)

Prevents authorization code interception attacks

Uses code_verifier and code_challenge

Required for OAuth 2.0 in mobile applications

OpenID Connect (OIDC)
Identity layer built on top of OAuth 2.0

Adds authentication to OAuth's authorization

Provides id_token (JWT) with user identity claims

Standard userinfo endpoint for profile data

JWT (JSON Web Token)
Common format for access tokens

Self-contained with claims (expiration, issuer, audience)

Can be validated without calling authorization server

Signed to prevent tampering

