Introduction to SOAP Web Services

What is SOAP?

SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol) is a protocol-based web service communication standard that follows strict rules and guidelines for exchanging structured information.
SOAP vs REST - Key Differences

Communication Protocol:
REST APIs follow HTTP protocols (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)

SOAP web services follow SOAP protocol with its own set of standards

Request/Response Format:
REST: Primarily uses JSON format (lightweight, easy to parse)

SOAP: Uses XML format exclusively for both requests and responses

Security:
REST: Only POST requests send data securely in body; GET requests expose data in URL

SOAP: All requests are POST methods - data always sent securely in the body, never exposed in URL

Message Structure:
REST: Flexible structure following HTTP conventions

SOAP: Rigid structure requiring envelope, header, and body elements

When to Use SOAP?

Enterprise-level applications requiring high security

Financial transactions and banking systems

Applications requiring ACID compliance

Legacy system integrations

Scenarios requiring built-in error handling (WS-ReliableMessaging)

