Click New and add the Node.js installation folder (e.g., C:\Program Files\nodejs).

Click OK on all windows.

2.3. Install Newman Globally
Use npm (Node Package Manager) to install Newman:
text

npm install -g newman

On macOS/Linux you might need sudo:
text

sudo npm install -g newman

Verify installation:
text

newman - version

2.4. Install HTML Reporter Plugin
To generate professional HTML reports, install the newman-reporter-html plugin globally:
text

npm install -g newman-reporter-html

---

3. Running a Collection with Newman - Essential Assets
Before running a collection from the command line, you must export the required assets from the Postman app.
3.1. What to Export
Collection (as .json file):
In Postman, click the ... next to your collection → Export → choose "Collection v2.1".

Environment (as .json file):
Click the ... next to an environment → Export.

Globals (as .json file):
Click the "Globals" button in the top‑right corner → Export.

Data file (CSV or JSON) - if you use data‑driven testing:
Place the file in a known folder.

3.2. Critical File Naming Rule
No spaces in file names.
Spaces are interpreted as argument separators by the terminal. Use underscores (_), hyphens (-), or camelCase.
Example: my_collection.json ✅ My Collection.json ❌

3.3. The Basic Newman Run Command
text
newman run my_collection.json

3.4. Full Command with All Options (No Table - Bulleted List)
The following flags can be combined in a single command:
-e or --environment – path to the exported environment .json file.

-g or --globals – path to the exported globals .json file.

-d or --iteration-data – path to the data file (CSV or JSON) for data‑driven runs.

-n or --iteration-count – number of iterations (overrides data file).

-r or --reporters – reporter to use (e.g., html, junit, cli).

Example of a complete command:
text
newman run Library-API-Tests.json -e UAT-Environment.json -g Team-Globals.json -d book-data.csv -r html

---

4. Generating Detailed HTML Reports
4.1. Why HTML Reports?
Console output is useful for real‑time debugging but not for long‑term analysis or sharing.

HTML reports provide:

A single dashboard with all test results.

Request and response bodies for each iteration.

Response times and status codes.

Clear pass/fail indicators.

4.2. Command to Generate HTML Report
text
newman run collection.json -e environment.json -d data.csv -r html

By default, the report is saved in a newman/ folder inside your current working directory.

Custom path and filename (advanced):
text

newman run collection.json -r html - reporter-html-export /custom/path/report.html

4.3. Typical Report Content
Total number of iterations.

Total number of assertions (pass/fail).

Breakdown by request: method, URL, headers, request body, response body.

Execution time for each request.

---

5. Integrating Newman with Jenkins (CI/CD)
5.1. Installing and Starting Jenkins
Download Jenkins: From the official website - get the generic Java .war file.

Run Jenkins from terminal:
text

java -jar jenkins.war - httpPort=9090

(Using port 9090 avoids conflicts with other services on port 8080.)

Access Jenkins: Open a browser to http://localhost:9090 and complete the setup (unlock with initial password, install suggested plugins, create admin user).

5.2. Creating a Freestyle Jenkins Job
New Item → Enter a name → Select Freestyle project → OK.

Build section:

For Windows: Add build step "Execute Windows batch command".

For macOS/Linux: Add build step "Execute shell".

Paste your Newman command into the command box.

Set the working directory - Jenkins runs from its own workspace by default. Use cd to change to the folder where your collection, environment, and data files are stored:
text

cd /path/to/your/project newman run my_collection.json -e my_env.json -d my_data.csv -r html

Save the job.

5.3. Running the Job and Viewing Results
Click Build Now on the job page.

Click the build number (e.g., #1) → Console Output to see the live Newman output.

The HTML report will be generated inside your project folder (as defined by the cd command).

---

6. Parameterized Jenkins Jobs for Multiple Environments
A powerful real‑world requirement is to run the same test suite against different environments (QA, UAT, Staging, Production) without changing the job configuration.
6.1. How It Works (Step by Step)
Export each environment from Postman as a separate .json file.
Use a consistent naming convention, e.g.:

QA-Postman-Env.json

UAT-Postman-Env.json

Make the Jenkins job parameterized:

In job configuration, check "This project is parameterized".

Click Add Parameter → Choice Parameter.

Name: ENVIRONMENT

Choices: (one per line)
text

QA UAT

Modify the Newman command to use the $ENVIRONMENT variable:
text

cd /path/to/your/project newman run my_collection.json -e "$ENVIRONMENT-Postman-Env.json" -d test-data.csv -r html

Run with parameters:

Click Build with Parameters.

Select the desired environment (e.g., UAT) from the dropdown.

Click Build.
Jenkins substitutes UAT-Postman-Env.json automatically.

6.2. Precondition for Success
No hardcoded values in your Postman requests or tests.
All environment‑specific data (base URLs, API keys, database names) must be stored as environment variables and referenced as {{variableName}}.

---

7. Team Collaboration with Git and Postman
When multiple team members work on the same Postman collection, use version control concepts (forking, pull requests, code reviews) to avoid conflicts.
7.1. Forking a Collection
Fork = create a personal copy of a team collection.

How to fork: In Postman, click the ... next to a collection → Create a fork.
You can now safely make changes in your fork without affecting the main collection.

7.2. Pull Request (PR) Workflow
Make changes in your forked collection (e.g., add new tests, fix assertions).

Create a pull request:
Click the ... on your fork → Create pull request. Add a title and description.

Assign reviewers: Select team members who should review your changes.

Review process:

Reviewers receive a notification.

They open the PR and go to the Changes tab to see exactly what lines were added/modified.

They can add comments on specific lines of code.

The PR author addresses the comments and pushes new commits to the fork (PR updates automatically).

Approval and merge:

Reviewers click Approve when satisfied.

The PR author clicks Merge to integrate changes into the main collection.

Best practice: Check "Delete source branch after merging" to keep the workspace clean.

7.3. Postman's Native Git Integration
Recent Postman versions allow you to connect a collection directly to a GitHub repository.

You can perform commits, pushes, pulls, and branch management from within Postman - bridging the gap between API testing and developer workflows.

---

8. Postman Monitors - Scheduled Cloud Execution
Monitors allow you to schedule a collection to run on Postman's cloud infrastructure, without needing a CI server.

Typical use case: Run a smoke test suite every morning at 8 AM to verify critical APIs are healthy before the team starts work.

8.1. Creating a Monitor
In Postman, click the ... next to a collection → Monitor Collection.

Name: Give it a descriptive name (e.g., "Daily Smoke Tests").

Collection & Environment: Select the collection and the environment (e.g., UAT).

Schedule: Choose frequency (e.g., "Weekly" → Monday to Friday → 08:00 AM).

Alerting: Enter email addresses to send failure notifications to.

Region: Select the Postman region from which to run (choose "Automatic" for most cases).

Additional settings:

Stop monitor after a number of consecutive failures.

Retry on failure.

Timeout settings.

Click Create Monitor.

8.2. Viewing Monitor Results
Go to the Monitors tab in Postman.

Click on a monitor to see its run history, logs, and detailed results.

---

9. Other Useful Postman UI Components (History, Trash, Runner)
These components help manage your testing activity.
9.1. History
Located in the left sidebar.

Shows a log of all requests sent from Postman (including those from collection runs, monitors, and manual requests).

Use cases:

Debugging a request that failed earlier.

Re‑using a previous request without rebuilding it.

Understanding what API calls were made during a test run.

9.2. Trash
When you delete a collection, environment, or other entity, it is moved to Trash (not permanently deleted immediately).

You can restore accidentally deleted items from the Trash.

Best practice: Periodically review the Trash and empty it only when you are certain the items are no longer needed.

9.3. Postman Runner (GUI)
The Runner is the graphical interface for running collections inside Postman.

It is useful for:

Quick exploratory runs during development.

Visualising data‑driven tests with CSV/JSON preview.

Debugging tests before exporting them to Newman.

How to open: Click the Runner icon (rocket) at the bottom right of the Postman window.

---

10. Interview Questions & Best Practices
10.1. Common Interview Questions
Q1: What is Newman, and why is it used?
A: Newman is the command‑line runner for Postman. It is used to execute Postman collections from the terminal, enabling automated API testing in CI/CD pipelines such as Jenkins, GitLab CI, or GitHub Actions.
Q2: How do you handle multiple environments (QA, UAT, Prod) in a Jenkins job that runs Newman?
A: Export each environment as a separate .json file. In Jenkins, create a Choice Parameter named ENVIRONMENT. In the Newman command, replace the static environment file with $ENVIRONMENT-Postman-Env.json. Jenkins substitutes the chosen value at runtime.
Q3: How do you generate an HTML report from Newman, and why is it important?
A: Install newman-reporter-html and add -r html to the command. The HTML report is important because it provides a readable, shareable document that includes request/response bodies, making debugging and stakeholder reporting much easier.
Q4: How can you run the same collection against different data sets?
A: Use the -d flag with a CSV or JSON data file. Newman will iterate over each row/record, replacing variables defined in the collection.
Q5: How do you collaborate with a team on a Postman collection?
A: Use Postman's forking and pull request workflow. Each team member forks the main collection, works in their fork, creates a PR, and after review, the changes are merged back.
10.2. Key Best Practices
Never hardcode values - always use environment or global variables for base URLs, tokens, etc.

Write atomic tests - each test script should verify one specific condition.

Use meaningful test names - e.g., "POST /user - returns status 201 and user ID".

Version control everything - export all collections, environments, and globals as JSON and store them in Git.

Integrate early in the pipeline - run Newman tests as part of every pull request build to catch regressions immediately.

Keep file names free of spaces - use underscores or hyphens to avoid command‑line errors.

---

