Comprehensive Guide: API Automation Testing with Postman for E-Commerce Applications - - draft
Source Analysis & Learning Objectives
This guide is based on a practical tutorial demonstrating end-to-end API automation for an e-commerce platform using Postman. The key learning objectives include:
Understanding session tokens and authentication flows

Automating API requests with dynamic data passing

Handling file uploads through API calls

Implementing proper test assertions

Cleaning up test data to maintain system integrity

---

Core Concepts
Session Tokens & Authentication
What is a Session Token?
A unique identifier generated upon successful login

Must be included in subsequent API requests for authentication

Typically valid for 30–40 minutes (implementation-dependent)

Proves to the backend that the request comes from an authenticated user

How Authentication Works:
Step 1: User provides credentials (email/password)

Step 2: Server validates credentials and generates a token

Step 3: Client receives token in response body

Step 4: All subsequent requests include token in Authorization header

Step 5: Server validates token before processing each request

Common Headers for Token Transmission:
Authorization: Bearer <token> (most common)

Authorization: Token <token>

Custom headers like x-auth-token

Why Dynamic Test Data Matters
Problem with Static Test Data:
Products may be deleted or modified

Tests fail when assuming existence of specific data

Repeated test runs create data pollution

Solution: Dynamic Data Creation
Create required data before using it

Pass data between API calls using variables

Clean up data after test completion

---

API Workflow for E-Commerce Testing
Complete Business Flow
text
Login → Create Product → Create Order → View Order Details → Delete Product

Rationale for Each Step:
Login: Obtain authentication token and user ID

Create Product: Generate test data under your control

Create Order: Place order using newly created product

View Order Details: Verify order was created correctly

Delete Product: Clean up test data

---

HTTP Methods & Their Uses
POST: Create new resource - examples include Login, Create Product, Create Order

GET: Retrieve resource - example is View Order Details

DELETE: Remove resource - example is Delete Product

---

Postman Implementation Details
Collection Variables Setup
Purpose: Store and share data across multiple requests in a collection
Common Variables Created:
token – Authentication token from login

userId – User identifier from login response

productId – ID of newly created product

orderId – ID of newly created order

productName – Name of the product (can have default value)

Login Request Implementation
Endpoint: POST /api/ecom/auth/login
Request Body (JSON):
json
{
    "userEmail": "your_email@example.com",
    "userPassword": "YourPassword123@"
}

Test Script for Login:
javascript
const jsonData = pm.response.json();
pm.expect(jsonData.message).to.eql("Login Successfully");
pm.collectionVariables.set("token", jsonData.token);
pm.collectionVariables.set("userId", jsonData.userId);

Key Learning Points:
Validate response message before extracting data

Store token and userId for reuse

Use pm.collectionVariables.set() for cross-request data sharing

Create Product Request
Endpoint: POST /api/ecom/product/add-product
Important Distinction - FormData vs JSON:
Most APIs accept JSON payloads

File uploads require FormData encoding

FormData sends key-value pairs (similar to HTML forms)

Required FormData Fields:
productName – Name of product (example: "Automation Product")

productAddedBy – User ID of creator (use {{userId}})

productCategory – Main category (example: "fashion")

productSubCategory – Sub-category (example: "shirts")

productPrice – Product price (example: "11500")

productDescription – Product description (example: "Product description text")

productFor – Target audience (example: "women")

productImage – Product image file (file upload)

Headers Required:
Authorization: {{token}}

Content-Type: multipart/form-data (automatically set by Postman)

File Upload Configuration in Postman:
Select "form-data" body type

For file field, change type from "text" to "file"

Click "Select Files" and choose from your system

Postman Settings for File Uploads:
Navigate to Settings → General

Enable "Allow reading files outside working directory" if needed

Or place files in Postman's default file directory

Test Script for Create Product:
javascript
const jsonData = pm.response.json();
pm.collectionVariables.set("productId", jsonData.productId);
pm.expect(jsonData.message).to.eql("Product Added Successfully");

Create Order Request
Endpoint: POST /api/ecom/order/create-order
Request Body (JSON):
json
{
    "orders": [
        {
            "country": "India",
            "productOrderedId": "{{productId}}"
        }
    ]
}

Understanding the Orders Array:
Square brackets [] indicate an array

Multiple products can be ordered together

Each order object in array gets its own order ID

Use index [0] to access first order ID

Test Script:
javascript
const jsonData = pm.response.json();
pm.collectionVariables.set("orderId", jsonData.orders[0]);
pm.expect(jsonData.message).to.eql("Order Placed Successfully");

View Order Details Request
Endpoint: GET /api/ecom/order/get-orders-details
Query Parameter:
?id={{orderId}}

Headers Required:
Authorization: {{token}}

Test Script with Validation:
javascript
const jsonData = pm.response.json();
pm.expect(jsonData.data.productName).to.eql(pm.collectionVariables.get("productName"));

Why Validate Product Name?
Confirms the correct order details are returned

Ensures the product you created matches what was ordered

Provides end-to-end verification

Delete Product Request
Endpoint: DELETE /api/ecom/product/delete-product/{{productId}}
URL Structure:
Path parameter (not query parameter)

Product ID is part of URL path

No request body needed

Headers Required:
Authorization: {{token}}

Test Script:
javascript
pm.test("Status code is 200", function () {
    pm.response.to.have.status(200);
});

Why Deletion is Important:
Prevents database pollution from repeated test runs

Maintains clean test environment

If 100 test runs create 100 products, deletion keeps system clean

Good testing practice: clean up what you create

---

Postman Test Scripts Deep Dive
Test Script Execution Order
Request is sent to server

Response is received

Test scripts execute automatically

Assertions are evaluated

Results appear in Test Results tab

Common Assertion Patterns
Status Code Validation:
javascript
pm.test("Status code is 200", () => {
    pm.response.to.have.status(200);
});

Response Body Validation:
javascript
pm.test("Response contains expected message", () => {
    const jsonData = pm.response.json();
    pm.expect(jsonData.message).to.eql("Expected Message");
});

Data Extraction with Validation:
javascript
const jsonData = pm.response.json();
pm.expect(jsonData.message).to.eql("Login Successfully");
pm.collectionVariables.set("token", jsonData.token);

Variable Scopes in Postman
Global scope - All collections, all environments. Use for base URLs, common credentials.

Collection scope - All requests in a specific collection. Use for flow-specific data (token, IDs).

Environment scope - All requests using selected environment. Use for environment-specific configs.

Local scope - Single request only. Use for temporary calculations.

---

Dynamic Data Passing Flow
Complete Data Flow Diagram (Text Representation)
text
[Login Request]
      ↓
  token, userId (stored in collection variables)
      ↓
[Create Product Request]
      ↓
  productId (stored)
      ↓
[Create Order Request] ← uses productId
      ↓
  orderId (stored)
      ↓
[View Order Details] ← uses orderId, token
      ↓
[Delete Product] ← uses productId, token

Using Variables in Requests
In URL:
text
https://api.example.com/delete-product/{{productId}}

In Headers:
text
Authorization: {{token}}

In Request Body (JSON):
json
{
    "productOrderedId": "{{productId}}"
}

In FormData:
Field value: {{userId}}

---

Handling Different Data Formats
JSON (application/json)
Characteristics:
Structured data format

Supports nested objects and arrays

Most common for modern APIs

Postman Configuration:
Body type: "raw"

Format: "JSON"

Write valid JSON syntax

FormData (multipart/form-data)
Characteristics:
Key-value pair format

Supports file uploads

Similar to HTML form submission

Postman Configuration:
Body type: "form-data"

Add key-value pairs

Toggle between "text" and "file" for values

When to Use FormData:
File/image uploads required

API explicitly expects form-urlencoded format

Legacy API integrations

---

Error Handling & Debugging
Common Errors and Solutions
401 Unauthorized:
Cause: Missing or invalid token

Solution: Verify token is being set correctly from login response. Check header name matches API expectation.

403 Forbidden:
Cause: Token expired or invalid permissions

Solution: Re-authenticate to get fresh token.

400 Bad Request - Missing Product ID:
Cause: productId not passed correctly

Solution: Verify variable name matches (case-sensitive). Check variable is set before use.

File Upload Not Working:
Cause: Postman file permissions issue

Solution: Enable file read setting or move file to Postman directory.

Debugging Techniques
1. Console Logging:
javascript
console.log(pm.collectionVariables.get("token"));
console.log(pm.response.json());

2. Postman Console:
View → Show Postman Console

See request/response details

Check variable values at runtime

3. Response Validation Before Extraction:
javascript
const jsonData = pm.response.json();
if (jsonData.token) {
    pm.collectionVariables.set("token", jsonData.token);
} else {
    console.error("Token not found in response");
}

---

Best Practices for API Test Automation
Never hardcode test data - Use variables for all dynamic values. Create data before using it. Don't assume existing data will always be available.

Validate at every step - Verify each request succeeded before proceeding. Check response messages match expectations. Validate data extraction worked.

Clean up test data - Delete created resources after test completion. Prevents database bloat. Makes tests repeatable.

Use descriptive test names - Example: pm.test("Login should return success message", () => {...}) and pm.test("Product ID should be extracted from response", () => {...})

Keep tests independent - Each test run should create its own data. Don't rely on data from previous runs. Clean up even if test fails (use Postman's prerequest and test scripts).

Collection Runner execution order - Requests execute in the order they appear in collection. Test scripts run after each request. Variables persist across all requests in run.

---

Real-World Interview Questions
Q1: How do you handle authentication tokens in Postman that expire during a test run?
Answer: Implement a pre-request script that checks token expiration and automatically re-authenticates if needed. Store token creation timestamp alongside the token, compare with current time, and refresh if approaching expiration.
Q2: What's the difference between query parameters and path parameters? When would you use each?
Answer:
Path parameters are part of URL path (e.g., /users/123). Used to identify specific resources.

Query parameters appear after ? (e.g., /users?role=admin). Used for filtering, sorting, or pagination.

Q3: Why create a product before placing an order instead of using existing products?
Answer: Using existing products creates test fragility. Products might be deleted, renamed, or unavailable. Creating your own product ensures: test data exists when needed, no interference from other tests, and complete control over test conditions.
Q4: How would you test file upload functionality without manual intervention each time?
Answer:
Place test files in a consistent directory

Use Postman's file path capability with relative paths

In CI/CD, use environment variables for file paths

Consider base64 encoding for smaller files as JSON

Q5: What assertions would you add beyond status code validation?
Answer:
Response structure validation (expected fields present)

Data type validation (string, number, array)

Business logic validation (prices calculated correctly)

Error message validation for negative tests

Response time assertions (< 500ms)

---

Common Pitfalls to Avoid
Forgetting Authorization Header - Symptom: 401 errors on all requests after login. Fix: Add Authorization: {{token}} header to every authenticated request.

Variable Name Mismatches - Symptom: Variables appear empty in requests. Fix: Check spelling and case sensitivity (productId vs productid).

Assuming Order of Execution - Symptom: Variables not available when needed. Fix: Run collection in correct sequence; use Collection Runner.

Not Validating Before Extraction - Symptom: Script errors when response structure changes. Fix: Check response status and expected fields before accessing properties.

Hardcoding File Paths - Symptom: Tests work on one machine, fail on another. Fix: Use relative paths or environment variables for file locations.

