Comprehensive Guide to GraphQL - - Draft 1
Important Note
These notes are based on educational content for learning purposes. All examples and concepts are used for illustrative purposes to help understand GraphQL fundamentals.

---

Part 1: Understanding GraphQL and Its Purpose
What is GraphQL?
GraphQL is a query language and server-side runtime created by Facebook in 2012 and open-sourced in 2015

It allows clients to request exactly the data they need - nothing more and nothing less

GraphQL is not a database - it does not store any data

It acts as a runtime that executes queries against your existing data sources

GraphQL serves as an intermediary layer between your frontend and backend systems

Data Sources GraphQL Can Connect To
REST APIs

SQL databases

NoSQL databases

Legacy systems

CSV files

Any other data source you can write code to access

The Problem with Traditional REST APIs
How REST APIs typically work:
Multiple endpoints exist for different domains

Each endpoint returns a fixed, predefined JSON response structure

The frontend must call multiple endpoints and parse each response

The server determines what data comes back, not the client

Real-World Example - Character Web Series Platform:
A client wants a homepage showing four specific pieces of information:
Character name and status (alive or dead)

Character location with coordinates and name

Latest episode broadcast date for that character

List of all other episodes featuring that character

The REST API approach to build this page:
First API call goes to a character details endpoint - this returns name, status, gender, species, age, origin, and many other fields

The frontend only needs name and status from this response, so it must parse the entire JSON to extract just these two fields

Second API call goes to a location details endpoint - this returns location name, population, coordinates, creation date, and more

The frontend only needs location name and coordinates, again requiring parsing of excess data

Third API call goes to an episode details endpoint to get the latest episode broadcast date

Fourth API call goes to get the complete list of all episodes for that character

Problems identified with REST approach:
Problem 1 - Over-fetching
Each API returns 10 to 20 fields but the frontend needs only 1 or 2 fields

This wastes bandwidth and processing power

Frontend developers must write parsers to extract specific fields from large JSON responses

Problem 2 - Performance issues
Four separate network calls are required to load a single page

Each call adds network latency (round-trip time)

Multiple calls increase the chance of failures

Page load time becomes the sum of all four API calls

Problem 3 - Increased complexity
Frontend needs parsers for each different API response

Error handling must be implemented for each call separately

Coordinating four asynchronous responses adds complexity

Real-life examples of this problem:
E-commerce websites load catalogs, profiles, recommendations, and footer details from multiple endpoints

Facebook loads posts, ads, profile information, and sidebar content from many different API calls

Any complex dashboard or homepage requires multiple API calls

How GraphQL Solves These Problems
The Single Endpoint Architecture:
GraphQL exposes exactly one endpoint (for example, /graphql)

All requests, regardless of what data they need, go to this same endpoint

Instead of calling four different REST endpoints, you send one query to the GraphQL endpoint

How a GraphQL query works:
You send a query that describes exactly what data you need

Example query asks for: character name, character status, location, dimension, and broadcast date

The GraphQL server receives this query and understands exactly what fields to fetch

The server talks to all necessary backend systems (character API, location API, episode API)

The server collects all the data and returns a single JSON response containing only the requested fields

The key difference from REST:
REST returns the entire response from each endpoint - you get everything whether you need it or not

GraphQL returns only what you ask for - no more, no less

In REST you write parsers to extract data; in GraphQL you get exact data directly

How GraphQL knows what data to fetch:
Backend developers write resolver functions for each field

A resolver for characterName knows how to fetch the character name from the character API or database

A resolver for locationName knows how to fetch location data

When you request specific fields, GraphQL calls only the resolvers for those fields

Performance Benefits
Instead of 4 separate REST API calls, you make 1 GraphQL call

One network round-trip instead of four

The GraphQL server can fetch data from multiple sources in parallel

Response time is often similar to a single REST API call

Frontend receives all needed data in one consolidated response

Is GraphQL a REST Replacement?
Important understanding:
GraphQL is not a replacement for REST APIs

GraphQL sits on top of your existing REST APIs, databases, and legacy systems

Your existing REST APIs still exist and continue to work

GraphQL acts as an optimization layer that improves performance and flexibility

You can gradually introduce GraphQL into an existing REST-based architecture

When Should You Use GraphQL?
GraphQL is well-suited for:
High-traffic e-commerce websites

Social media platforms (Facebook, Twitter)

Applications with complex data relationships

Mobile apps where bandwidth is limited

Dashboards that show multiple types of data on one screen

When frontend teams need flexibility to request different data for different screens

GraphQL may not be necessary for:
Simple websites that show only one type of data per page

Internal admin panels with low traffic

Small projects where performance is not a major concern

When your team lacks resources to implement and maintain GraphQL

Real-world adoption examples:
Facebook created GraphQL and uses it extensively

Netflix uses similar patterns for API optimization

Shopify provides a GraphQL API for storefront development

GitHub offers a public GraphQL API

Many high-performance e-commerce companies now use GraphQL

GraphQL Can Do More Than Fetch Data
Mutations for creating and updating data:
REST uses POST to create a character and a different POST to create an episode

GraphQL can create a character AND create an episode in a single mutation

One endpoint call can write to multiple backend systems

Similarly, updates and deletions can be combined

Example of combined mutation:
You want to create a new character and also create a new episode

Instead of two separate POST calls to two different REST endpoints

One GraphQL mutation describes both creation operations

GraphQL calls the character creation resolver and the episode creation resolver

Both operations complete in one network round-trip

Official GraphQL Definition
GraphQL has two main components:
A query language - The syntax you use to describe what data you need

A server-side runtime - The system that executes your queries against your existing data

Important clarification:
GraphQL is NOT a database engine

GraphQL does NOT store any data

GraphQL is NOT a storage engine of any kind

GraphQL is backed entirely by your existing code and data systems

---

Part 2: GraphQL Schema and Types
What is a GraphQL Schema?
A schema is a contract between the frontend and backend

It lists ALL the possible data the GraphQL server can provide

Before writing any query, you must check the schema to know what is available

Backend developers design the schema and write resolvers for each field

If a field is not in the schema, you cannot request it

How to Explore a GraphQL Schema
GraphQL Explorer UI:
Most GraphQL servers automatically provide an interactive Explorer UI

Access it by opening your GraphQL endpoint URL in a browser

Example URL: https://rahulshettyacademy.com/GQ/GraphQL

The Explorer shows complete documentation of all available types and fields

Using the Explorer effectively:
Open the Docs section to see all root types (Query and Mutation)

Click on any type to see its available fields

Each field shows its return type and any arguments it accepts

Required arguments are marked with an exclamation mark !

You can write and test queries directly in the Explorer

Core Components of a GraphQL Schema
1. Types
A type is similar to a class in object-oriented programming

Each type represents a domain object (Character, Location, Episode)

Types contain fields that describe the object's properties

2. Fields
Fields are individual pieces of data within a type

Examples of fields in a Character type: name, status, gender, location

Each field has a return type (String, Int, Boolean, or another Object type)

3. Arguments
Arguments allow you to filter or specify which data to return

Passed inside parentheses after a field name

Example: characterDetails(id: 8) – here id is the argument with value 8

Required arguments are marked with !

Scalar Types (Basic Data Types)
String
Represents text values

Example: "Rahul", "alive", "Male"

Int
Represents integer numbers (whole numbers)

Example: 8, 42, 1891

Float
Represents decimal numbers

Example: 12.5, -1.5

Boolean
Represents true or false values

Example: true, false

ID
Represents a unique identifier

Often used for primary keys

Object Types (Custom Types)
Definition:
Object types contain multiple fields grouped together

Fields can be scalar types OR other object types

Example of a CharacterDetails type:
text
type CharacterDetails {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  status: String
  gender: String
  location: LocationDetails
}

Understanding the exclamation mark !:
The ! means the field is non-nullable (required)

id: ID! means every character must have an ID, and it cannot be null

name: String! means every character must have a name

status: String (without !) means status can be null (maybe unknown)

Nested Types
Important concept:
Fields can return other object types, not just scalar values

This creates a graph structure where types connect to each other

Example of nesting:
A Character type has a location field

The location field returns a LocationDetails type

The LocationDetails type has its own fields: name, dimension, coordinates

How to request nested data:
You cannot simply ask for location alone because location is an object, not a scalar

You must specify which fields of the location object you want

Example: location { name dimension }

Reading a Schema - Practical Example
Step-by-step approach to understanding any GraphQL schema:
First, look at the root Query type - this shows all available read operations

Identify the type you need (for example, characterDetails)

Click on that type to see what fields it returns

Note which fields require arguments (look for parentheses)

Check which arguments are required (look for !)

For each field, note its return type

If a return type is another object type, click into it to see its fields

Build your query by selecting only the fields you need

Example schema exploration:
You see in the Docs:
text
characterDetails(id: Int!): CharacterDetails

This tells you:
There is an operation called characterDetails

It takes an argument called id of type Int

The ! means the id argument is required

It returns a type called CharacterDetails

You then click on CharacterDetails and see:
text
CharacterDetails {
  id: ID!
  name: String!
  status: String
  gender: String
  location: LocationDetails
}

This tells you:
You can request id, name, status, gender, and location fields

location returns another object type LocationDetails, so you must request its sub-fields

Why the Schema is Critical
Without the schema, you have no idea what data you can request

The schema acts as documentation that never goes out of date

The schema provides automatic validation - GraphQL will reject requests for fields that don't exist

Changes to the schema are backward-compatible - you can add fields without breaking existing queries

---

Part 3: Writing GraphQL Queries
Basic Query Structure
The general format for any GraphQL query:
text
query {
  operationName(argumentName: argumentValue) {
    field1
    field2
    field3
  }
}

Breaking it down:
query keyword tells GraphQL this is a read operation

operationName is the name of the operation as defined in the schema

(argumentName: argumentValue) passes arguments to filter or specify data

The curly braces { } contain the fields you want to receive

Simple Example - Get Character by ID
Query:
text
query {
  characterDetails(id: 8) {
    name
    status
  }
}

What this query does:
Calls the characterDetails operation

Passes id: 8 as an argument (get the character with ID 8)

Requests only the name and status fields

GraphQL returns a JSON response containing exactly these two fields

Response:
text
{
  "data": {
    "characterDetails": {
      "name": "Rahul",
      "status": "alive"
    }
  }
}

Notice:
The response structure matches the query structure exactly

No extra fields are returned

No parsing is needed on the frontend

Requesting More Fields
Query:
text
query {
  characterDetails(id: 8) {
    name
    status
    gender
    species
  }
}

Response includes all four requested fields:
text
{
  "data": {
    "characterDetails": {
      "name": "Rahul",
      "status": "alive",
      "gender": "male",
      "species": "human"
    }
  }
}

Dynamic Responses - Adding Fields Later
Key advantage of GraphQL:
You can add fields to your query without any backend changes

Suppose your frontend previously asked for name and status

Now you also need gender

Simply add gender to your query – no need to modify the API

The resolver for gender already exists (or if it doesn't, GraphQL returns an error)

Multiple Operations in One Query
You can request different types of data in a single query:
text
query {
  characterDetails(id: 8) {
    name
    status
  }
  locationDetails(id: 8) {
    name
    dimension
  }
  episode(id: 8) {
    name
    airDate
  }
}

What happens:
GraphQL executes all three operations in parallel when possible

All responses are combined into one JSON object

One network call fetches character, location, and episode data

Response structure:
text
{
  "data": {
    "characterDetails": { "name": "Rahul", "status": "alive" },
    "locationDetails": { "name": "India", "dimension": "123" },
    "episode": { "name": "The Rahul Show", "airDate": "1950" }
  }
}

Nested Queries - Requesting Related Data
When a field returns another object type:
text
query {
  characterDetails(id: 8) {
    name
    status
    location {
      name
      dimension
    }
  }
}

Important rule:
You cannot just write location by itself because location is an object

You must specify which fields of the location object you want

If you don't, GraphQL returns an error

Correct way - with nested fields:
text
location {
  name
  dimension
  coordinates {
    latitude
    longitude
  }
}

Queries That Return Lists
Getting all characters that match a filter:
text
query {
  characters(filter: { name: "Rahul" }) {
    info {
      count
    }
    result {
      name
      gender
      status
    }
  }
}

Understanding the structure:
characters returns an object that contains info and result

info contains metadata like total count

result is a list (array) of character objects

Each character object in the result has name, gender, and status fields

Why you need to specify fields inside result:
result returns a list of Character objects

Character is an object type, not a scalar

You must specify which fields of each character you want

Query Variables - Making Queries Reusable
The problem with hardcoded values:
characterDetails(id: 8) hardcodes the ID 8

If you need character ID 9, you must change the query

This makes queries non-reusable

The solution - query variables:
Step 1 - Define the variable at the top of the query:
text
query GetCharacter($characterId: Int!) {
  characterDetails(id: $characterId) {
    name
    status
  }
}

Step 2 - Pass the variable value separately:
text
{
  "characterId": 8
}

What each part means:
query GetCharacter – names the query (optional but recommended)

($characterId: Int!) – declares a variable named characterId of type Int, required

$characterId – uses the variable in the argument

The variable value is provided in a separate JSON object

Benefits of using variables:
The query text remains the same for different inputs

You can reuse the same query with different variable values

Variables prevent string concatenation and injection risks

Variables provide type safety

Multiple Variables Example
Query with two variables:
text
query GetCharacterAndEpisode($charId: Int!, $epId: Int!) {
  characterDetails(id: $charId) {
    name
    status
  }
  episode(id: $epId) {
    name
    airDate
  }
}

Variables:
text
{
  "charId": 8,
  "epId": 11
}

Using Variables for Complex Filters
Query with filter variable:
text
query GetCharactersByName($name: String!) {
  characters(filter: { name: $name }) {
    result {
      name
      status
    }
  }
}

Variables:
text
{
  "name": "Rahul"
}

Query Best Practices
Always name your queries (example: query GetCharacterDetails) – helps with debugging

Use variables for all dynamic values - never hardcode values inside the query string

Request only the fields you actually need - this is the core benefit of GraphQL

For nested objects, always specify which sub-fields you want

Use the Explorer's auto-complete to avoid typos in field names

Test queries in the Explorer before moving to Postman or code

---

Part 4: GraphQL Mutations
What Are Mutations?
Mutations are operations that modify data on the server

Use mutations for create, update, and delete operations

The syntax is similar to queries but uses the mutation keyword

Unlike REST where different HTTP methods indicate operation type, GraphQL uses the operation name

Create Mutation - Adding New Data
Basic structure of a create mutation:
text
mutation {
  createLocation(location: {
    name: "Australia",
    type: "Southern Region",
    dimension: "234"
  }) {
    id
  }
}

Breaking it down:
mutation keyword indicates this is a write operation

createLocation is the mutation name as defined in the schema

location: is an argument that expects an input object

The input object contains all the fields needed to create a location

The { id } part asks GraphQL to return the ID of the newly created location

Why request fields in a mutation:
Mutations can return data after the operation completes

You typically want to get back the ID of the newly created record

You might also want to get back the entire created object to use immediately

Create Character Mutation Example
Mutation:
text
mutation {
  createCharacter(character: {
    name: "Robin Vayne",
    status: "deceased",
    species: "Human",
    gender: "male",
    image: "image_url",
    origin: "fictional",
    locationId: 15
  }) {
    id
    name
  }
}

Response:
text
{
  "data": {
    "createCharacter": {
      "id": 14,
      "name": "Robin Vayne"
    }
  }
}

Important notes about required fields:
Check the schema to see which fields are required (marked with !)

If you omit a required field, GraphQL returns an error

Optional fields can be omitted

Understanding Input Types
What is an input type?
An input type is a special object type used only for mutation arguments

It defines the shape of data you must provide to create or update something

Input types are separate from regular object types

Example from schema:
The createCharacter mutation expects an argument of type CharacterInput

CharacterInput is an input type containing fields like name, status, species, etc.

You cannot use regular object types for mutation arguments - only input types

Delete Mutation
Deleting a single item:
text
mutation {
  deleteLocation(locationId: 15) {
    deletedLocations
  }
}

Deleting multiple items at once:
text
mutation {
  deleteLocations(locationIds: [17, 14]) {
    deletedLocations
  }
}

Understanding list syntax:
[17, 14] is an array (list) of location IDs

The deletedLocations field returns the count of successfully deleted items

Some schemas also return the IDs of deleted items

Multiple Mutations in One Request
Creating multiple related items in a single mutation:
text
mutation {
  createLocation(location: {
    name: "New Zealand",
    type: "Island",
    dimension: "123"
  }) {
    id
  }
  createCharacter(character: {
    name: "Baskin Robbins",
    status: "alive",
    species: "Human",
    gender: "male",
    locationId: 16
  }) {
    id
  }
}

What happens:
Both mutations execute in sequence or parallel (depends on implementation)

One network call performs both create operations

The response includes the results of both mutations

Using Variables in Mutations
Mutation with variables:
text
mutation CreateData($locationName: String!, $characterName: String!) {
  createLocation(location: {
    name: $locationName,
    type: "Southern",
    dimension: "500"
  }) {
    id
  }
  createCharacter(character: {
    name: $characterName,
    status: "alive",
    species: "Alien",
    gender: "male",
    locationId: 16
  }) {
    id
  }
}

Variables:
text
{
  "locationName": "South Africa",
  "characterName": "Pascal Robin"
}

Mutation Response Patterns
Return the created object:
text
mutation {
  createCharacter(character: {...}) {
    id
    name
    status
    location {
      name
      dimension
    }
  }
}

Return only the ID:
text
mutation {
  createCharacter(character: {...}) {
    id
  }
}

Return a success message or count:
text
mutation {
  deleteLocations(locationIds: [17, 14]) {
    deletedLocations
  }
}

Mutation Best Practices
Always request the ID of created records so you can reference them later

For updates, request the updated fields to confirm the change

Use variables for all dynamic values in mutations

Check the schema to know which fields are required (look for !)

For delete mutations, consider returning the count or IDs of deleted items

Combine related mutations into one request when possible

