Part 5: Testing GraphQL with Postman
Setting Up a GraphQL Request in Postman
Step-by-step setup:
Step 1 - Create a new request:
Click New → Request in Postman

Give it a name (example: "Get Character Details")

Save it to a collection

Step 2 - Set the HTTP method:
All GraphQL requests use the POST method

Select POST from the dropdown

Step 3 - Enter the endpoint URL:
Paste your GraphQL endpoint URL

Example: https://rahulshettyacademy.com/GQ/GraphQL

Remove any query parameters from the URL if present

Step 4 - Configure the Body tab:
Click on the Body tab

Select GraphQL as the body type (not raw or JSON)

Postman will automatically recognize this as a GraphQL request

Step 5 - Write your query:
In the Query section, paste your GraphQL query or mutation

Example:

text
query GetCharacter($charId: Int!) {
  characterDetails(id: $charId) {
    name
    status
    gender
  }
}

Step 6 - Add variables (if using):
In the GraphQL Variables section, add your variables as JSON

Example:

text
{
  "charId": 8
}

Step 7 - Send the request:
Click the Send button

The response appears in the bottom panel

Complete Postman Example
Request configuration:
Method: POST

URL: https://rahulshettyacademy.com/GQ/GraphQL

Body type: GraphQL

Query:
text
query GetCharacterDetails($charId: Int!) {
  characterDetails(id: $charId) {
    name
    status
    gender
    location {
      name
      dimension
    }
  }
}

Variables:
text
{
  "charId": 8
}

Expected response:
text
{
  "data": {
    "characterDetails": {
      "name": "Rahul",
      "status": "alive",
      "gender": "male",
      "location": {
        "name": "India",
        "dimension": "123"
      }
    }
  }
}

Mutation in Postman
Request configuration (same as query):
Method: POST

Same endpoint URL

Body type: GraphQL

Mutation query:
text
mutation CreateNewLocation($locName: String!, $locType: String!) {
  createLocation(location: {
    name: $locName,
    type: $locType,
    dimension: "999"
  }) {
    id
  }
}

Variables:
text
{
  "locName": "Canada",
  "locType": "Northern Region"
}

Using Postman Features for GraphQL
Environment variables:
Store your GraphQL endpoint in a collection variable

Example variable: {{baseUrl}}/GraphQL

Switch between development and production endpoints easily

Pre-request scripts:
Generate dynamic values for variables before sending the request

Example: generate a unique name for a new character

Tests scripts:
Write tests to validate GraphQL responses

Check that the response contains expected data

Validate that no errors are present in the response

Example test script:
text
pm.test("Response has data", function () {
    var jsonData = pm.response.json();
    pm.expect(jsonData.data).to.not.be.null;
});
pm.test("No GraphQL errors", function () {
    var jsonData = pm.response.json();
    pm.expect(jsonData.errors).to.be.undefined;
});

Finding the Endpoint from the Explorer
Using browser developer tools:
Open the GraphQL Explorer in your browser

Open Developer Tools (F12)

Go to the Network tab

Execute a query in the Explorer

Look for the network request - it shows the exact endpoint URL and request body

Copy this URL and body structure to Postman

Postman Collection Structure for GraphQL
Suggested organization:
Create a collection named "GraphQL_API"

Create a folder named "Queries" for all read operations

Create a folder named "Mutations" for all write operations

Within each folder, save individual requests for specific operations

Example: "Get Character by ID", "Get All Characters", "Create Character", "Delete Location"

Important Notes for Postman
All GraphQL requests use POST method - never use GET for GraphQL in Postman

Do not put the query in URL parameters - always use the request body

The GraphQL body type in Postman automatically sets the correct Content-Type header

You can also use raw JSON with {"query": "...", "variables": {...}} if needed

Postman's GraphQL mode provides syntax highlighting and auto-completion

