Part 6: GraphQL Explorer (GraphiQL) Detailed Guide
What is GraphQL Explorer?
A built-in web interface that comes with most GraphQL servers

Often called GraphiQL (GraphQL + graphical) or GraphQL Playground

Provides an interactive environment to explore the schema and test queries

Available by simply opening the GraphQL endpoint URL in a web browser

Accessing the Explorer
Navigate to your GraphQL endpoint URL in any modern web browser

Example: https://rahulshettyacademy.com/GQ/GraphQL

The Explorer interface loads automatically if the server has introspection enabled

Main Sections of the Explorer
Left panel (Query Editor):
Where you write your GraphQL queries and mutations

Supports syntax highlighting

Provides auto-completion as you type

Shows syntax errors with red underlines

Right panel (Response Viewer):
Shows the JSON response after executing a query

Formatted and collapsible for easy reading

Bottom panel (Variables):
Separate section for defining query variables

Variables are written as JSON

Automatically applied to the query

Docs panel (usually on the right side):
Shows the complete schema documentation

Click on any type to see its fields

Search functionality to find specific types or fields

Using the Explorer to Learn a Schema
Step 1 - Open the Docs:
Click on the "Docs" button (usually on the right side)

This shows the root types: Query, Mutation, and Subscription

Step 2 - Explore the Query type:
Click on "Query" to see all available read operations

Each operation shows its arguments and return type

Example: characterDetails(id: Int!): CharacterDetails

Step 3 - Explore a specific type:
Click on CharacterDetails to see its fields

Each field shows its return type

Fields that return other types are clickable - you can navigate deeper

Step 4 - Check required arguments:
Look for exclamation marks ! – these indicate required fields

Example: id: Int! means the id argument is required

If an argument has no !, it is optional

Writing Queries in the Explorer
Using auto-completion:
Start typing query { and press Ctrl+Space (or Cmd+Space on Mac)

A list of available operations appears

Select an operation and the Explorer adds the structure

Adding fields:
After typing the operation and opening curly braces, press Ctrl+Space again

The Explorer shows all available fields for that return type

Select the fields you need

Using the "Add" button (if available):
Some Explorers have an "Add" button next to fields

Clicking it adds the field to your query

Testing Queries
Write your query in the left panel

Click the "Execute" button (play icon) or press Ctrl+Enter

The response appears in the right panel

If there are errors, they appear in the response panel with details

Using the Explorer for Debugging
Syntax errors:
The Explorer underlines syntax errors in red

Hover over the underline to see the error message

Validation errors:
If you request a field that doesn't exist, the Explorer shows an error before execution

Example error: "Cannot query field 'xyz' on type 'CharacterDetails'"

Argument errors:
If you omit a required argument, the Explorer shows an error

Example error: "Field 'characterDetails' argument 'id' of type 'Int!' is required"

Exporting Queries from Explorer
Once you have a working query, copy it from the Explorer

Paste it into Postman or your code

Also copy any variables you defined

Limitations of the Explorer
The Explorer is for development and testing only - not for production use

Some servers disable introspection (the feature that powers the Explorer) in production for security

The Explorer does not support authentication in all configurations

Complex queries with many fields can be slow to render

