Part 7: GraphQL Best Practices and Common Pitfalls
Best Practices for Writing Queries
Always request only needed fields:
This is the fundamental benefit of GraphQL

Resist the temptation to copy-paste full schemas

Each field you request adds to response size and resolver execution time

Use named queries for production:
Instead of query {, use query GetUserProfile {

Named queries help with debugging and monitoring

Names appear in server logs and performance metrics

Use variables for dynamic values:
Never concatenate strings to build queries

Variables prevent injection attacks

Queries with variables can be cached more effectively

Fragment for reusable field sets:
If you request the same fields in multiple places, use a fragment

Example:

text
fragment CharacterBasicInfo on CharacterDetails {
  name
  status
  gender
}

Then use it: ...CharacterBasicInfo

Set reasonable depth limits:
Deeply nested queries can cause performance problems

Work with backend teams to understand safe depth limits

Best Practices for Schema Design
Design types around business domains:
Do not mirror database tables directly

Create types that match how the frontend needs to consume data

Use non-null types appropriately:
Fields that should always have a value should be marked with !

But be careful - making everything non-null reduces flexibility

If a field can legitimately be missing or unknown, don't mark it non-null

Add descriptions to schema:
Every type and field should have a description

Descriptions appear in the Explorer documentation

Good descriptions reduce the need for external documentation

Version without versioning:
Never remove or rename existing fields - this breaks clients

Instead, add new fields and deprecate old ones

Use the @deprecated directive on fields you plan to remove

Performance Best Practices
Use DataLoader for batching:
Without DataLoader, GraphQL can cause the N+1 problem

Example: Getting 10 characters and their locations could make 11 database calls

DataLoader batches and caches requests to solve this

Implement query complexity analysis:
Some queries are more expensive than others

Calculate complexity based on number of fields and depth

Reject queries that exceed a complexity threshold

Use persisted queries in production:
Instead of sending full query strings, send a query ID

The server stores approved queries

Reduces request size and improves security

Enable response caching where possible:
GraphQL typically uses POST requests which bypass HTTP caching

Consider using GET for queries (if server supports it) to leverage CDN caching

Or implement application-level caching

Security Best Practices
Authentication before resolution:
Check authentication in the context before any resolver runs

Do not rely on individual resolvers to check authentication

Authorization at field level:
Different fields may have different permission requirements

Example: salary field should only be visible to managers

Check permissions inside each resolver

Rate limiting based on complexity:
Simple queries and complex queries cost different amounts of resources

Rate limit based on calculated complexity, not just number of requests

Disable introspection in production:
Introspection allows anyone to see your complete schema

While useful for development, it exposes internal structure

Disable introspection in production for sensitive APIs

Common Pitfalls and How to Avoid Them
Pitfall 1 - Requesting too many fields:
Problem: Frontend requests every field of a type because it's easier

Result: Large responses, slow performance

Solution: Train teams to request only needed fields; consider query cost analysis

Pitfall 2 - Not using variables:
Problem: Hardcoding values in query strings

Result: No query reuse, caching ineffective, injection risks

Solution: Always use variables for dynamic values

Pitfall 3 - Forgetting nested field selections:
Problem: Requesting a field that returns an object type but not specifying sub-fields

Result: GraphQL error "Field 'location' of type 'LocationDetails' must have a selection of subfields"

Solution: Always look at return types; if not scalar, add sub-fields

Pitfall 4 - Overusing fragments:
Problem: Creating fragments for everything

Result: Queries become harder to read and debug

Solution: Use fragments only when the same field set appears in multiple places

Pitfall 5 - Not checking schema first:
Problem: Guessing field names or arguments

Result: Validation errors, wasted time

Solution: Always check the schema documentation before writing queries

Pitfall 6 - Assuming GraphQL is always faster:
Problem: Expecting GraphQL to magically solve all performance issues

Result: Disappointment when complex queries are slow

Solution: Understand that GraphQL shifts complexity to the server; implement proper optimizations

Pitfall 7 - Ignoring error handling:
Problem: Assuming successful responses always contain data

Result: Frontend crashes when partial errors occur

Solution: Check for errors array in response; handle partial data gracefully

