Part 8: Common Interview Questions and Answers
Beginner Level Questions
Q1: What is GraphQL and why was it created?
A: GraphQL is a query language for APIs created by Facebook to solve over-fetching and under-fetching problems in their mobile apps. It allows clients to request exactly the data they need from a single endpoint.

Q2: How is GraphQL different from REST?
A: REST uses multiple endpoints (one per resource) with HTTP methods to indicate operation type. The server determines response structure. GraphQL uses a single endpoint where clients specify exactly what data they need in the request body, and the server returns only that data.

Q3: What are the main operations in GraphQL?
A: Query (for reading data, like GET in REST), Mutation (for creating, updating, or deleting data, like POST/PUT/DELETE in REST), and Subscription (for real-time data, like WebSockets).

Q4: What is a GraphQL schema?
A: A schema is a contract between client and server that defines all available data types, fields, and operations. It acts as documentation and enables validation of queries before execution.

Q5: What is a resolver?
A: A resolver is a function that tells GraphQL how to fetch data for a specific field. Resolvers can fetch from databases, REST APIs, legacy systems, or any other data source.

Intermediate Level Questions
Q6: Explain the difference between over-fetching and under-fetching.
A: Over-fetching means receiving more data than needed (a REST API returns 20 fields but you only need 2). Under-fetching means not receiving enough data in one call, requiring multiple calls to gather all needed information. GraphQL solves both by letting clients request exactly what they need.

Q7: What are query variables and why use them?
A: Query variables allow you to pass values separately from the query string. Benefits include: reusability of the same query with different inputs, prevention of string concatenation/injection attacks, type safety, and better caching.

Q8: What is the N+1 problem in GraphQL?
A: The N+1 problem occurs when a resolver makes a separate database call for each item in a list. Example: fetching 10 characters (1 call) then fetching the location for each character (10 calls) results in 11 total calls. This is solved using DataLoader which batches and caches requests.

Q9: How do you handle errors in GraphQL?
A: GraphQL returns a 200 HTTP status code even when errors occur. Errors are placed in an errors array in the response body. Partial responses are possible – successful fields return data even if other fields fail. Clients must check for the errors array.

Q10: Can you use GraphQL with existing REST APIs?
A: Yes, absolutely. GraphQL is often used as a layer on top of existing REST APIs. Resolvers can call your existing REST endpoints. GraphQL does not replace REST - it adds an optimization layer.

Q11: What is introspection?
A: Introspection is the feature that allows GraphQL clients to query the schema for information about available types, fields, and operations. It powers tools like GraphiQL Explorer. Can be disabled in production for security.

Q12: What is a fragment in GraphQL?
A: A fragment is a reusable set of fields. When the same fields appear in multiple places in a query, you can define a fragment once and use it multiple times using the ...FragmentName syntax.

Advanced Level Questions
Q13: How do you implement authentication and authorization in GraphQL?
A: Authentication is typically handled in the context object - validate the token before any resolver runs. Authorization can be field-level - check permissions inside each resolver or using schema directives. Some implementations use middleware for common authorization patterns.

Q14: What are the downsides or limitations of GraphQL?
A: GraphQL has a learning curve; caching is more complex than REST (since all requests go to one endpoint); file uploads require special handling; complex queries can overwhelm servers if not properly limited; not ideal for simple applications.

Q15: How do you version a GraphQL API?
A: GraphQL APIs are typically not versioned in the traditional sense (no /v1/, /v2/). Instead, you add new fields and deprecate old ones using the @deprecated directive. Existing queries continue to work because you never remove fields.

Q16: What is a persisted query?
A: A persisted query is a query that is stored on the server. The client sends only a query ID instead of the full query string. Benefits include smaller request sizes, improved security (queries are whitelisted), and faster execution.

Q17: How do you test GraphQL APIs?
A: Testing approaches include: unit tests for individual resolvers; integration tests for queries/mutations against a test database; schema testing to ensure schema changes don't break clients; Postman/Newman for API automation; GraphQL Inspector for schema validation.

Q18: What is the difference between input types and regular object types?
A: Regular object types are used for responses (data coming out). Input types are used for mutation arguments (data going in). Input types cannot contain fields that are object types - they can only contain scalar types or other input types.

