5. The API Testing Lifecycle and Mindset
5.1 The API Contract - Your Most Important Document
Before you write a single test, you must obtain the API contract from the development team. It is the blueprint for testing.
The contract must clearly specify:
The full endpoint URL (base URL + resource path).

The HTTP method (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.).

Required headers (e.g., Content-Type, Authorization).

Query parameters and path parameters (names, types, example values, whether required or optional).

Request body schema: field names, data types, required/optional fields, example JSON/XML.

Response structure for success (200) and for various errors (400, 401, 404, 500).

Possible status codes and their meanings.

Without a contract, you are testing blindly. Always ask: "Can you share the API contract / Swagger / OpenAPI specification?"
5.2 What Exactly to Verify in an API Test?
Status Codes:

200 OK - General success.

201 Created - Resource successfully created (often for POST).

400 Bad Request - Client sent invalid data (e.g., missing required field).

401 Unauthorized - Authentication failed or missing.

403 Forbidden - Authenticated but not allowed.

404 Not Found - Resource does not exist.

500 Internal Server Error - Server‑side bug.

Response Body:

All mandatory fields are present.

Data types are correct (e.g., lat is a number, name is a string).

Actual values match expectations (e.g., after update, address is changed).

Error messages are clear and helpful (not just "error").

Response Headers:

Content-Type should match what you asked for (usually application/json).

Content-Length (if relevant).

Performance:

Response time should be within a reasonable limit (e.g., < 500ms for most endpoints). This can be measured with tools or in Postman.

Negative Testing (very important):

Send requests with missing required parameters.

Send invalid data (e.g., wrong data type, malformed JSON).

Use a non‑existent place_id.

Use an incorrect API key.

Expect proper error codes (400, 404, 401) instead of 500.

5.3 End‑to‑End Test Flow Example
A typical full scenario for the Google Maps API:
Add a new place → get place_id.

Get that place → verify all details.

Update the address of that place.

Get again → confirm address has changed.

Delete the place.

Get again → confirm it fails (404 or "not found").

This sequence ensures that all CRUD operations work correctly together.

