6. Variables and Environments
What are Variables?
Variables store reusable values (e.g., base URL, API keys, book IDs).
Syntax: {{variableName}} inside requests and scripts.

Variable Scopes (from lowest to highest precedence)

Global - available across all workspaces and collections. Set via pm.globals.set().
Collection - available only within that collection. Set via pm.collectionVariables.set().
Environment - active only when a specific environment is selected. Set via pm.environment.set().
Data - available only during a collection run; values come from CSV/JSON file.
Local - temporary, exists only during a single script execution. Set via pm.variables.set() (local scope).

Precedence rule: Data > Environment > Collection > Global > Local (when retrieving using pm.variables.get()).
Environments - Switching Configurations

An environment is a named set of variables.
You can switch between environments (e.g., "Development", "Staging", "Production") without editing requests.

Example Environment: Staging
baseUrl = https://staging.api.bookstore.example
apiKey = stg_abc123

Example Environment: Production
baseUrl = https://api.bookstore.example
apiKey = prod_xyz789

Using Variables in Requests

URL: {{baseUrl}}/books
Headers: X-API-Key: {{apiKey}}
Body: { "isbn": "{{dynamicIsbn}}" }

Script Examples for Variables
// Set environment variable
pm.environment.set("bookId", responseBody.bookId);
// Get a variable (resolves in scope order)
let base = pm.variables.get("baseUrl");
// Set global variable
pm.globals.set("globalTimeout", 5000);

---

7. Scripting in Postman - The pm Object
The pm (Postman) object provides access to request, response, variables, and test functions.
Pre‑request Script (runs before the request is sent)
Use cases:
Generate unique test data (e.g., timestamp‑based ISBN).
Clean up existing resources (if a record exists, delete it first).
Set dynamic headers or body values.

Example - generate unique ISBN and ensure no conflict:
// Generate unique ISBN using timestamp
const uniqueIsbn = "isbn_" + Date.now();
pm.variables.set("isbn", uniqueIsbn);
// Expected bookId = isbn + "42" (assuming aisle is fixed to "42")
const expectedBookId = uniqueIsbn + "42";
// Check if book already exists
pm.sendRequest({
    url: pm.variables.get("baseUrl") + "/books/" + expectedBookId,
    method: 'GET'
}, function (err, res) {
    if (res.code === 200) {
        // Delete existing book
        pm.sendRequest({
            url: pm.variables.get("baseUrl") + "/books/" + expectedBookId,
            method: 'DELETE'
        });
    }
});
Test Script (runs after the response is received)

Use cases:
Verify status code.
Parse JSON response and check values.
Validate business logic (e.g., ID concatenation).
Store values for subsequent requests.

Example - tests for "Add Book" response:

// 1. Status code check
pm.test("Status code is 201", () => {
    pm.response.to.have.status(201);
});
// 2. Parse response
const jsonData = pm.response.json();
// 3. Check success message
pm.test("Success message is correct", () => {
    pm.expect(jsonData.message).to.eql("Book added successfully");
});
// 4. Validate ID generation logic
const expectedId = pm.variables.get("isbn") + "42";
pm.test("bookId is concatenation of isbn and aisle", () => {
    pm.expect(jsonData.bookId).to.eql(expectedId);
});
// 5. Store bookId for later requests
pm.environment.set("currentBookId", jsonData.bookId);
Handling Errors Gracefully (Try‑Catch Equivalent)

Postman does not have traditional try‑catch, but you can use conditional checks and the assertion library.

pm.test("Safely parse response", () => {
    try {
        const data = pm.response.json();
        if (data.bookId) {
            pm.expect(data.bookId).to.be.a('string');
        }
    } catch (e) {
        console.log("Error parsing JSON: " + e.message);
    }
});

