8. Data‑Driven Testing
Data‑driven testing allows you to run the same API request with multiple input values from an external file (CSV or JSON).
Steps to Perform Data‑Driven Testing

Create a data file (e.g., books.csv):
title,isbn,aisle,author 
"API Basics","aaa","111","Alice" "Advanced APIs","bbb","222","Bob" "Security Testing","ccc","333","Carol"
Modify your request to use variables - the variable names must match the column headers:
{ "title": "{{title}}", "isbn": "{{isbn}}", "aisle": "{{aisle}}", "author": "{{author}}" }
Run the collection with the data file:
Click "Runner" (or "Run collection")
Select your collection
Under "Data File", choose books.csv
The number of iterations will automatically match the number of rows
Click "Run"
How Data Variables Work

For each iteration, Postman reads one row from the file.
The values are available via {{columnName}} in the request, and via pm.iterationData.get("columnName") in scripts.
Data variables have the highest precedence during a collection run.

Example Script Using Data Variables

const isbnFromData = pm.iterationData.get("isbn");
pm.test("ISBN from data is used", () => {
    pm.expect(pm.response.json().bookId).to.include(isbnFromData);
});

