11. Testing SOAP Web Services with Postman

Although Postman is best known for REST, it also supports SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol).
REST vs. SOAP - Key Differences

REST uses only HTTP; supports JSON, XML, plain text; stateless; no WSDL required.

SOAP can use HTTP, SMTP, TCP; only XML; can be stateful; requires a WSDL.

How to Test a SOAP Service in Postman

Set HTTP method to POST.

Enter the SOAP endpoint URL (e.g., https://example.com/soap/calculator).

Add headers:

Content-Type: text/xml

SOAPAction (if required by the service)

Body: choose "raw" and "XML" type, then paste the SOAP envelope.

Example SOAP Request (Number to Words):
xml
<soap:Envelope xmlns:soap="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/">
  <soap:Body>
    <NumberToWords xmlns="http://www.dataaccess.com/webservicesserver/">
      <ubiNum>123</ubiNum>
    </NumberToWords>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>

Parsing SOAP XML Responses in Tests

Postman does not automatically parse XML into JSON.

Use string matching (simple but fragile).

Use the xml2Json function (available in Postman sandbox) to convert XML to JSON.

Example test script:
javascript
// Convert XML response to JSON
const jsonResponse = xml2Json(pm.response.text());
// Access values (structure depends on the SOAP service)
const result = jsonResponse['soap:Envelope']['soap:Body']['NumberToWordsResponse']['NumberToWordsResult'];
pm.test("SOAP response contains correct conversion", () => {
    pm.expect(result).to.include("one hundred twenty three");
});

Tip: For complex SOAP testing, consider saving the conversion logic as a reusable library in your collection.

