Part 1: What Is a Web Service?

Core definition - A way for two different applications or devices to communicate over the internet, regardless of their programming language or platform.
Real‑world example (airline + hotel integration)
British Airways (Java website) wants to show hotels in Paris after flight booking

Hotels.com (.NET website) has hotel data but cannot directly share code due to platform differences

Solution: a web service acts as a bridge

British Airways sends only the destination ("Paris") to the web service

The web service talks to Hotels.com backend

Hotels.com returns the list of hotels

British Airways receives and displays the hotels - no code integration needed

Other everyday examples
Twitter feed on a website → uses Twitter API

Google Maps location on a business site → uses Google Maps API

PayPal checkout on any site → uses PayPal API

Mobile app login using web credentials → API call to web backend

---

Part 2: Two Main Types of Web Services

SOAP Web Services

Full name - Simple Object Access Protocol

Message format - XML (Extensible Markup Language)

Nature - Strict, standardized protocol

Requires a contract - WSDL (Web Services Description Language)

Typical use - Traditional enterprise systems (banking, healthcare, airlines)

Error handling - Built‑in <fault> element in the response

REST API Web Services

Full name - REpresentational State Transfer

Message format - Usually JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)

Nature - Architectural style, not a strict protocol (more flexible)

Contract - Not mandatory; OpenAPI/Swagger is optional

Typical use - Modern web apps, mobile backends, microservices

Why learn both?
Old companies (15–20+ years) often have only SOAP services

New companies may use only REST

Many real‑world organisations use both depending on the need

---

Part 3: SOAP Protocol - Detailed Structure

SOAP message layers (no table)
Envelope - The root container; must be present in every SOAP message. It defines where the service is hosted (endpoint).

Header - Optional part; holds metadata such as session cookies, authentication tokens, transaction IDs.

Body - Required part; contains the actual request data or the response data.

Fault - Error element that appears in the response when something goes wrong (e.g., invalid input, service error).

Example of a SOAP request (calculator - add two numbers)
text
Envelope starts here
  Header (optional – can be empty)
  Body
    Add operation
      intA = 2
      intB = 3

Example of a SOAP response
text
Envelope
  Body
    AddResponse
      AddResult = 5

If an error occurs, the response contains a <fault> element explaining the problem.

---

Part 4: WSDL - The Service Contract (SOAP Only)

What is WSDL?
Web Services Description Language

An XML document that completely describes a SOAP web service

Pronounced "wiz‑dull" or spelled "W‑S‑D‑L"

Why do you need WSDL?
Without it, you don't know what operations exist

You don't know which parameters to send or their data types

You cannot test a SOAP service - the WSDL is mandatory

Real‑world analogy - Restaurant menu
WSDL = the menu (lists everything you can order)

SOAP message = your spoken order (the actual communication)

Web service = the kitchen (prepares and returns the result)

What information does a WSDL provide?
Definitions - Root element, container for everything, defines service name

Types - Data types used by the service (e.g., integer, string, custom objects) - makes them reusable

Message - Defines the data exchanged between provider and consumer - each operation typically has an input and an output message

PortType - Groups one request and one response into an operation - a service can have many operations

Binding - Concrete details on how the operation is transmitted (SOAP over HTTP, HTTP GET, HTTP POST, etc.)

Service - Tells clients where to access the service (endpoint URL) and which port to use

How to get the WSDL from a SOAP service - add ?wsdl to the base service URL.
Example from a calculator service WSDL
Operations found: Add, Subtract, Multiply, Divide

Add operation expects: two integers (intA, intB)

Returns: an integer result (AddResult)

Important - You do not need to memorise the XML syntax. SoapUI will parse the WSDL and show you the operations in a clean, easy‑to‑use interface.

---

Part 5: Critical Distinction - SOAP vs WSDL vs SoapUI

Many beginners confuse these three. Here is the clear difference:
SOAP - A communication protocol (a set of rules for message structure)

WSDL - An XML document that describes a SOAP service (the contract)

SoapUI - A testing tool used to test both SOAP and REST services

Restaurant analogy again
WSDL = Menu (describes what is available)

SOAP message = Your order (the communication)

Web service = Kitchen (prepares the food)

SoapUI tool = A food critic who tests everything

