Comprehensive API Testing Notes for Automation Testers (SDET) - Draft

1. Core API Concepts - Why APIs Exist

1.1 The Problem Without APIs

A hotel booking website (e.g., Marriott) may have its frontend and backend written in the same language (Java), so communication is seamless.

Two common real-world challenges appear:

Third‑party integration - Another website (e.g., Hotels.com) wants to display and book Marriott hotels without accessing Marriott's entire backend code. Sharing full source code is impossible for security and business reasons.

Technology mismatch - The frontend is rewritten in Angular/TypeScript while the backend remains in Java. Direct method calls between different programming languages are not technically feasible.

1.2 The API Solution

An API (Application Programming Interface) acts as an intermediary layer between the client (frontend) and the server (backend).

Communication happens over HTTP protocol, which is language‑agnostic and supported everywhere.

Data is exchanged in JSON or XML format - both are language‑independent representations.

The API receives a request, invokes the corresponding backend method, and returns a formatted response.

External parties (e.g., Hotels.com) only need the API endpoint - not the original source code.

1.3 Analogy for Interviews

Think of an API as a restaurant waiter.

The kitchen (backend) speaks one language.

Customers (clients) speak another.

The waiter takes orders (requests), communicates with the kitchen, and brings back food (responses) - without either side understanding the other's internal details.

---

2. REST API Fundamentals - What Every SDET Must Know

2.1 HTTP Methods and CRUD Operations

POST → Create (C in CRUD)

Used when sending new data to the server (e.g., adding a place, creating a booking).

Server typically generates a unique identifier.

Not idempotent - calling it multiple times creates multiple resources.

GET → Read (R in CRUD)

Used to retrieve existing information (e.g., fetching place details, getting user profile).

Request body is not sent; all data goes via URL and headers.

Idempotent - multiple identical calls return the same result.

PUT → Update (U in CRUD)

Used to replace an entire existing resource (e.g., updating an address, changing phone number).

Client provides the resource identifier.

Idempotent - repeated calls produce the same outcome.

PATCH → Partial Update

Used when only a subset of fields needs to be changed.

More bandwidth‑efficient than PUT for small updates.

DELETE → Delete (D in CRUD)

Used to remove a resource (e.g., deleting a place, cancelling a booking).

Idempotent - deleting a non‑existent resource usually returns an error but does not change the system state.

Important real‑project note:
Some APIs use POST for delete operations - always verify the API contract instead of assuming method conventions.
2.2 Endpoint Structure - Breaking Down the URL

A complete URL example:
https://rahulshettyacademy.com/maps/api/place/add/json?key=qaclick123
Components
Base URL / Domain - https://rahulshettyacademy.com
The server where the APIs are hosted.

Resource Path - /maps/api/place/add/json
Identifies which specific API endpoint is being called.

Query Parameters - ?key=qaclick123
Additional data used for filtering, authentication, or configuration.

How to identify parameter types
Query parameters

Start with ? after the resource path.

Multiple parameters are separated by &.

Example: ?key=qaclick123&place_id=abc123

Used for filtering, sorting, or passing credentials.

Path parameters

Embedded directly in the URL with forward slashes.

Example: /users/12345/orders – here 12345 is a path parameter.

Used to identify a specific resource within a collection.

2.3 Headers and Cookies - Metadata That Matters

Common headers
Content-Type - Indicates the format of the request body (e.g., application/json).
Missing or wrong value leads to 415 Unsupported Media Type.

Authorization - Carries credentials like Bearer tokens or API keys.
An expired token returns 401 Unauthorized.

Accept - Tells the server what response format the client expects (e.g., application/json).

Cookie - Used for session identification (e.g., sessionId=abc123).

Why headers matter in automation
Missing Content-Type causes request rejection.

Expired tokens in Authorization produce authentication failures.

Some APIs require custom headers like X-API-Key or X-Request-ID for tracking and debugging.

---

3. Google Maps API - Practical Example for End‑to‑End Testing

3.1 API Contracts (as described in typical training projects)

Add Place API (POST)
Purpose: Create a new place in the server.

Endpoint: https://rahulshettyacademy.com/maps/api/place/add/json

Query parameter: key=qaclick123

Request body (JSON) contains: location (lat, lng), accuracy, name, phone_number, address, types, website, language.

Response: Provides place_id (unique identifier), status, scope, reference.

Get Place API (GET)
Purpose: Retrieve details of an existing place.

Endpoint: https://rahulshettyacademy.com/maps/api/place/get/json

Query parameters: key=qaclick123 and place_id

Response: Returns the complete place details matching what was originally added.

Update Place API (PUT)
Purpose: Modify the address of an existing place.

Endpoint: https://rahulshettyacademy.com/maps/api/place/update/json

Query parameter: key=qaclick123

Request body:
json

{"place_id": "value", "address": "new address", "key": "qaclick123"}

Note: In this specific contract, only the address field can be updated.

Delete Place API (POST)
Purpose: Remove an existing place from the server.

Endpoint: https://rahulshettyacademy.com/maps/api/place/delete/json

Query parameter: key=qaclick123

Request body:
json

{"place_id": "value"}

Response: Returns status OK on successful deletion.

3.2 End‑to‑End Test Flow (Data Dependency Pattern)

Add Place → Capture the returned place_id.

Get Place → Verify that the details match what was sent.

Update Place → Change the address field.

Get Place again → Confirm that the address has been updated.

Delete Place → Remove the created place.

Get Place one more time → Verify that a failure (404 or error message) is returned.

Critical automation insight:
The place_id from the Add operation must be passed to Get, Update, and Delete operations. This demonstrates data dependency between API calls – a very common pattern in real projects.

---

4. API Test Automation Framework Design (SDET Focus)

4.1 Test Case Structure Using TestNG (Example Flow)

Setup (@BeforeClass)

Configure base URL, common query parameters (e.g., key=qaclick123), and content type.

Add Place test (@Test(priority=1))

Send POST request with the place payload.

Assert status code 200 and status "OK".

Extract place_id into a static variable.

Get Place test (@Test(priority=2, dependsOnMethods))

Use the extracted place_id as a query parameter.

Assert that the returned address matches the original.

Update Place test (@Test(priority=3))

Send PUT request with the same place_id and a new address.

Assert success message.

Delete Place test (@Test(priority=4))

Send DELETE (or POST) request with the place_id.

Assert status OK.

Get deleted Place test (@Test(priority=5))

Try to retrieve the same place_id.

Expect 404 or a failure status.

4.2 Property Transfer - SOAPUI vs Code

SOAPUI way
Use a Property Transfer test step.

Source: Add response, JSONPath place_id.

Target: Delete request, JSONPath place_id.

Code way (Rest Assured)
Extraction:
placeId = response.jsonPath().getString("place_id");

Reuse:
.queryParam("place_id", placeId)

Common mistake:
Hardcoding a place_id instead of transferring it dynamically – the test will fail on the second run because that ID no longer exists.
4.3 Best Practices for API Test Automation

Test Data Management
Never hardcode dynamic values (e.g., place_id) – always extract from responses.

Use properties files or environment variables for static data (base URL, API keys).

Use TestNG Data Providers to run the same test with different payloads.

Always clean up test data after execution - delete created resources in @AfterClass.

Validation Strategy
Minimum: Check status code (e.g., assertEquals(response.statusCode(), 200);).

Body checks: Validate critical fields like status and place_id.

Schema validation: Use JSON Schema Validator to ensure contract compliance.

Negative testing scenarios (must include)
Missing required fields in the request body.

Invalid API key (expect 401 or 403).

Malformed place_id (wrong format).

Deleting an already deleted resource.

Updating a non‑existent place.

4.4 Common Pitfalls (Interview Preparation)

Hardcoded place_id → Test fails on second run.
Solution: Extract and pass dynamically.

Ignoring status codes → Test may pass even when the server returns an error.
Solution: Always validate status code before checking the body.

No cleanup → Test data accumulates and causes false failures.
Solution: Delete created resources in teardown methods.

Sequential dependency without validation → If Add fails, all subsequent tests fail chaotically.
Solution: Use dependsOnMethods or a fail‑fast strategy.

Assuming 200 means success → Some APIs return 200 with an error message in the body.
Solution: Always parse the response body's status field.

---

5. Framework Design Considerations (Advanced SDET Level)

5.1 Hybrid Framework Components

Configuration Management
config.properties file storing base.url, api.key, timeout.

Environment‑specific configurations (dev, staging, production).

Maven profiles to switch between environments.

Payload Management
Separate Java classes as POJOs for request/response.

Builder pattern for constructing complex payloads.

External JSON files for large payloads, loaded via TestNG data providers.

Authentication Handling
API Key - passed as query parameter: .queryParam("key", apiKey).

Bearer Token - added as header: .header("Authorization", "Bearer " + token).

OAuth 2.0 - using Rest Assured's .auth().oauth2(accessToken).

Logging and Reporting
Use RestAssured.filters() with RequestLoggingFilter and ResponseLoggingFilter to log requests/responses.

ExtentReports for rich HTML execution reports.

Allure for reporting with attachments and test steps.

CI/CD Integration (Jenkins Pipeline Example)
groovy
stage('API Tests') {
    steps {
        sh 'mvn clean test -DsuiteXmlFile=api-test-suite.xml'
    }
    post {
        always {
            publishHTML([
                reportDir: 'target/surefire-reports',
                reportFiles: 'emailable-report.html'
            ])
        }
    }
}

---

6. Interview Questions - Scenario‑Based (with Answers)

Q1: Your API test passes locally but fails in CI/CD. What do you investigate?
Environment differences: base URL (dev vs staging), network proxies, authentication token expiry.

Database state: test data may exist locally but not in CI.

Rate limiting: CI IP addresses might be blocked or throttled.

Timeout settings: CI environments may be slower.

Q2: How do you handle API dependencies where one call's response is needed for another?
Extract required values using JsonPath.

Store them in instance variables or TestNG's ITestContext.

Pass between test methods using dependsOnMethods.

In BDD/Cucumber, use the scenario context to share data between steps.

Q3: The Add API returns 200 but place_id is empty. How would you debug?
Check the response body structure - the contract may have changed.

Verify that the place was actually created by calling Get API with a known ID.

Validate the request payload for missing mandatory fields.

Log the complete response (headers + body).

Confirm that the API key has write permissions.

Q4: How would you test the Update API independently without calling Add first?
Set up test data via database insertion (if the testing database is accessible).

Use a pre‑created test place_id stored in a configuration file.

Or have a setup method (@BeforeClass) that calls Add once and reuses the same ID across multiple update scenarios.

Q5: Explain idempotency with an example from these APIs.
DELETE and PUT should be idempotent.

Deleting the same place_id twice: first call returns OK, second call may return "place does not exist" but should not cause errors or side effects.

POST (Add) is not idempotent - each call creates a new place with a different place_id.

---

7. Quick Revision Cheat Sheet (No Tables)

7.1 HTTP Methods - Short Summary

POST → Create → Server generates ID → Response 201/200 + resource ID.

GET → Retrieve → No request body → Response 200 + resource data.

PUT → Replace full resource → Needs complete resource → Response 200/204.

PATCH → Partial update → Only changed fields → Response 200.

DELETE → Remove resource → Needs identifier → Response 200/204.

7.2 JSONPath Expressions - Frequently Used

$.place_id → Extract place_id from the root.

$.status → Extract status field.

$.location.lat → Extract nested latitude.

$..address → Recursive search for any address field.

$.types[0] → First element of the types array.

7.3 HTTP Status Codes - Must Know

200 OK → Success with response body.

201 Created → Resource successfully created.

204 No Content → Success, no response body (often for DELETE).

400 Bad Request → Invalid request (missing required field).

401 Unauthorized → Authentication failed.

403 Forbidden → Authenticated but no permission.

404 Not Found → Resource does not exist.

500 Internal Server Error → Backend failure.

7.4 Test Data Flow Pattern (Memory Aid)

Add → Extract place_id

Get using same ID (verify)

Update using same ID

Get again (verify update)

Delete using same ID

Get → expect 404 or failure

7.5 Interview Memory Aids

CRUD = POST (Create), GET (Read), PUT (Update), DELETE (Delete)

Idempotent methods: GET, PUT, DELETE (same result on repeated calls)

Non‑idempotent: POST (each call creates a new resource)

Authentication placement: Query param (?key=value), Header (Authorization), rarely in body.

Base URL vs Endpoint: Base = server location, Endpoint = specific API path.

7.6 Common TestNG Annotations for API Testing

@BeforeSuite → Global configuration, initialize reports.

@BeforeClass → Setup request specification, base URL.

@BeforeMethod → Reset test data before each test.

@Test → Main test logic with assertions.

@AfterMethod → Capture test status, log failures.

@AfterClass → Cleanup (delete created resources).

@AfterSuite → Flush reports, close connections.

7.7 Rest Assured Syntax - Quick Reference (Given‑When‑Then)

java
given()
    .queryParam("key", "qaclick123")
    .header("Content-Type", "application/json")
    .body(payload)
.when()
    .post("/maps/api/place/add/json")
.then()
    .statusCode(200)
    .body("status", equalTo("OK"))
    .extract().path("place_id");

