Building an Enterprise API Test Automation Framework: From SoapUI to CI/CD-Draft

1. Core Concept: Why a Framework for API Tests?

In real-world projects, manually executing API tests from GUI tools like SoapUI or Postman is not scalable, maintainable, or suitable for continuous integration.
1.1 The Problem with Tool-Only Execution

No external trigger - Tests run only from within the tool's interface.

Tool dependency - The tool must be installed on every machine where tests execute.

No CI integration - Cannot be triggered automatically by Jenkins after a code commit.

Limited reporting and scheduling - Lacks enterprise‑level reports, parallel runs, or cron‑based scheduling.

1.2 The Solution: A Standalone Java / TestNG Framework

Decouple test execution from the API tool.

Use the tool (e.g., SoapUI) only for designing test cases and save them as an XML project file.

Create a Java project that reads this XML file and executes the tests using the tool's public Java APIs.

Run the Java project from the command line, allowing any CI system to trigger it.

1.3 Real-World Scenario (SDET Perspective)

As an SDET, you design API tests in SoapUI and save the project. Your manager asks: "Can these tests run automatically from Jenkins after every code deploy?" The answer is yes - by building a Java framework that consumes the SoapUI XML project file, without needing SoapUI installed on the build machine.

---

2. Designing API Tests in SoapUI (Foundation)

The first practical step is to create reliable API test cases inside SoapUI and save the project.
2.1 Types of API Projects in SoapUI

SOAP Web Service - Imported via a WSDL URL (e.g., EmployeeManagementService WSDL).

REST API Service - Created manually from API documentation (no WSDL), like the Library API with endpoints /AddBook.php, /GetBook.php, /DeleteBook.php.

2.2 Building a REST API Test Project from Documentation

Given an API document (similar to the Library+API.docx example), you manually create the project in SoapUI.
Key details to extract from API documentation:
Base URI - e.g., http://216.10.245.166

Resource path - e.g., /Library/AddBook.php

HTTP method - POST, GET, etc.

Request payload - JSON body with fields (name, isbn, aisle, author)

Expected response - e.g., { "Msg": "successfully added", "ID": "bcd227" }

Steps in SoapUI:
Create a new REST project.

Add a new resource with the given path.

Set the HTTP method (POST/GET).

Provide the endpoint and request payload.

Add assertions (e.g., a "Contains" assertion for the text "successfully added").

2.3 Making Tests Robust: Key SoapUI Features for a Framework

Property Transfer - Extract dynamic values (like an ID from a response) and store them as test suite or project properties. Essential for end‑to‑end flows (add → capture ID → delete using that ID).

Groovy Script Assertions - Handle complex validations, such as iterating over a JSON array response to confirm a specific book exists.

Property Expansion - Use ${#TestSuite#propertyName} to parameterize endpoints and input data instead of hardcoding.

Best Practice: Always use property transfers for dynamic data. Never hardcode values that change between runs.

2.4 The SoapUI Project File (XML)

Saving a SoapUI project produces a single .xml file (e.g., LibraryAPI.xml, Employee.xml).

This XML contains all test suites, test cases, requests, assertions, and property transfers.

This XML file becomes the bridge between SoapUI and the Java framework.

---

3. The Java Framework: Executing SoapUI Tests Without the Tool

3.1 Prerequisite Setup (SDET Environment)

Java Installation & Environment Variables
Install JDK 8 or a later stable version.

Set the JAVA_HOME system variable to point to the JDK installation directory.

Add %JAVA_HOME%/bin to the PATH variable.

Verify with java -version in the command prompt.

Eclipse IDE Setup
Download Eclipse IDE for Java Developers.

Ensure Java is installed before opening Eclipse.

Creating a Java Project
File → New → Java Project (e.g., name: API_Framework).

Create a source folder (src) and packages for organization.

3.2 Importing SoapUI Libraries (JARs)

The Java project needs SoapUI's Java API JARs to parse and execute the XML project file.
Location of JARs - Inside the SoapUI installation directory, under the lib folder (e.g., C:\Program Files\SmartBear\SoapUI-5.3.0\lib).

Steps in Eclipse:

Right‑click project → Build Path → Configure Build Path → Libraries tab.

Click Add External JARs.

Select all JARs from the SoapUI lib folder.

Also add testng-<version>.jar (downloaded separately) to support TestNG.

Common Mistake: Forgetting to add soapui-x.x.x.jar or the TestNG JAR leads to compilation errors. Always include all dependencies.

3.3 Core Java Class: WsdlProject

The WsdlProject class (from SoapUI's API) is the entry point for loading the .xml project file.
java
import com.eviware.soapui.impl.wsdl.WsdlProject;
// Provide the absolute path to the SoapUI project XML file
WsdlProject project = new WsdlProject("C:\\path\\to\\LibraryAPI.xml");

What happens internally?
The WsdlProject object scans the XML, loads all test suites, test cases, and steps into memory. No SoapUI graphical interface is required.
3.4 Accessing and Executing Test Cases

Get a specific test suite by name:
java
WsdlTestSuite testSuite = project.getTestSuiteByName("Testing");

Get all test cases in a suite (loop over them):
java
int testCaseCount = testSuite.getTestCaseCount();
for (int i = 0; i < testCaseCount; i++) {
    WsdlTestCase testCase = testSuite.getTestCaseAt(i);
    TestCaseRunner testRunner = testCase.run(new WsdlTestRunContext(testCase), false);
    // Check results
}

Run a single test case by name:
java
WsdlTestCase testCase = testSuite.getTestCaseByName("GetEmployee");
TestCaseRunner runner = testCase.run(new WsdlTestRunContext(testCase), false);

3.5 Validating Execution Status

After running a test case, retrieve the status to determine pass/fail.
java
TestRunner.Status status = runner.getStatus();
if (status == TestRunner.Status.FINISHED) {
    System.out.println("Test Passed");
} else {
    System.out.println("Test Failed");
}

3.6 Handling Dynamic Data (Property Transfer in Java)

When a test step (e.g., addEmployee) returns a dynamic value (like an employee ID), you can extract it via code, but SoapUI's property transfer is simpler. Inside the SoapUI project, add a "Property Transfer" test step after the request to store the dynamic value into a test suite property. The Java code can then access that property from the WsdlProject or WsdlTestSuite context if needed, but typically the SoapUI test case manages it internally.

