4. Migrating to TestNG for Better Framework Capabilities

Executing SoapUI tests from a public static void main method works, but using TestNG offers significant advantages:
Annotations (@Test, @BeforeSuite, @AfterMethod)

Built‑in assertions (hard and soft)

Rich HTML/XML reports

Parallel execution, grouping, and data providers

Seamless integration with CI tools via testng.xml

4.1 Convert a Java Class to TestNG

Before (plain main method):
java
public static void main(String[] args) { ... }

After (TestNG style):
java
import org.testng.annotations.Test;
import org.testng.Assert;
public class LibraryAPITests {
    @Test
    public void addAndDeleteBook() {
        // Load project, run test cases, capture status
        Assert.assertEquals(runner.getStatus(), TestRunner.Status.FINISHED);
    }
}

4.2 Creating testng.xml

TestNG uses an XML file to define which test suites, classes, or methods to run.
xml
<!DOCTYPE suite SYSTEM "http://testng.org/testng-1.0.dtd">
<suite name="API Test Suite">
    <test name="Library API Tests">
        <packages>
            <package name="com.yourpackage.tests"/>
        </packages>
    </test>
</suite>

Right‑click the project → TestNG → Convert to TestNG to generate this file automatically (requires the TestNG plugin installed in Eclipse).

4.3 Installing the TestNG Plugin in Eclipse

Help → Eclipse Marketplace

Search for "TestNG"

Install and restart Eclipse.

---

5. Running Tests from the Command Line (CI/CD Ready)

Once the framework is ready (Java code + testng.xml + all JARs), you can execute it without any IDE.
5.1 Organising the Project Structure

text
ProjectRoot/
├── src/                # Java source files (.java)
├── bin/                # Compiled .class files (after compilation)
├── lib/                # All dependent JARs (SoapUI libs + testng.jar)
├── testng.xml          # TestNG suite file
└── LibraryAPI.xml      # SoapUI project file (or Employee.xml)

5.2 Compilation Command (Windows)

cmd
javac -classpath "lib/*" -d ./bin ./src/com/yourpackage/tests/*.java

-classpath lib/* – Includes every JAR from the lib folder.

-d ./bin – Places the compiled .class files into the bin folder.

./src/... – Path to the Java source files.

5.3 Execution Command

cmd
java -cp "bin;lib/*" org.testng.TestNG testng.xml

-cp – Classpath containing compiled classes (bin) and all JARs (lib/*).

org.testng.TestNG – TestNG's main class that runs the suite.

testng.xml – The TestNG configuration file.

SDET Tip: On Linux or macOS, use a colon (:) as the classpath separator instead of a semicolon (;).

5.4 What Happens During Execution

Compilation - Converts .java files to .class bytecode.

Execution - TestNG reads testng.xml, discovers test classes/methods, loads them using the classpath, and runs them. The SoapUI API loads the LibraryAPI.xml file internally to execute the test steps.

