Part 1: Web Services - Core Concepts

What Are Web Services?

A web service is a piece of business logic made accessible over a network using standard internet protocols (HTTP, HTTPS, SOAP, etc.)

It does not depend on any specific programming language - Java, Python, C#, JavaScript, or any other language can consume the same service

The service is hosted on a server at a specific endpoint (IP address + port + resource path)

Clients send requests (usually with input data) and receive responses (output data)

Real‑world analogy:
A web service is like an ATM machine - it provides a specific service (cash withdrawal, balance check) using a standard interface (card + PIN), regardless of which bank issued your card. The internal systems of the bank can be completely different, but the service works uniformly.
Why companies use web services:
They enable integration between different systems written in different languages

They hide internal implementation details

They allow reuse of the same business logic across web, mobile, and third‑party applications

Common interview question:
"What is the main benefit of web services over direct database access?"
Expected answer: Web services provide a controlled, language‑agnostic, and secure way to expose business logic. Direct database access would couple clients to the internal schema, create security risks, and make versioning extremely difficult.

---

SOAP vs REST - Key Differences (No Table)

SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol)
Is a strict protocol with built‑in standards for security (WS‑Security), transactions, and reliability

Uses only XML for message format - very verbose

Can work over multiple transport protocols: HTTP, SMTP, TCP, UDP

Requires a WSDL contract - the client must understand the service definition before calling it

Has built‑in error handling and ACID compliance support

Heavier performance due to XML parsing and envelope overhead

REST (Representational State Transfer)
Is an architectural style, not a protocol - it follows six guiding constraints

Typically uses JSON (lightweight) but can also use XML, plain text, HTML

Works only over HTTP/HTTPS - relies on HTTP verbs (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)

Does not require a formal contract - often documented via OpenAPI/Swagger

Much lighter and faster; preferred for microservices, mobile backends, and public APIs

Stateless by design - each request contains all necessary information

When to choose which:
Choose SOAP for banking, payment gateways, or legacy enterprise systems where strict contracts, built‑in security, and transaction support are mandatory.

Choose REST for modern web APIs, mobile apps, cloud services, and when performance and simplicity are priorities.

Common trick question:
"Is REST the same as HTTP?"
Correct answer: No. REST uses HTTP as a transport, but not every API that uses HTTP is RESTful. A truly RESTful API must also respect other constraints: statelessness, cacheability, uniform interface, layered system, and optionally HATEOAS.

---

WSDL - Web Services Description Language (for SOAP)

An XML document that acts as a contract between the service provider and the consumer

Describes everything a client needs to know:

What operations (methods) the service offers

What input parameters each operation expects (names, data types, structure)

What output (response) format will be returned

Where the service is physically located (endpoint URL)

Which protocols and transports are supported (HTTP, SMTP, etc.)

Practical example:
Imagine a restaurant. The WSDL is like the menu:
Menu lists all dishes (operations)

For each dish, it lists ingredients (input parameters)

It also describes how the dish is presented (output format)

The kitchen's location is the endpoint.

How testers use WSDL:
Obtain the WSDL URL from the development team or from a service registry.

Import the WSDL into a tool like SoapUI.

The tool automatically generates sample requests for each operation.

Testers send valid and invalid requests and validate responses against the WSDL definitions.

Troubleshooting tip:
If SoapUI fails to import a WSDL, check:
The WSDL URL is accessible from your browser (network or DNS issue).

The XML is well‑formed - use an online validator.

The WSDL may reference other XSD schemas via relative paths - convert them to absolute URLs or download locally.

---

Endpoints

An endpoint is the specific URL where a web service can be accessed.

Format example: http://api.mycompany.com/v1/payments/process

A single service may have multiple endpoints for different operations.

Components of an endpoint (breakdown):
Base URI: https://api.example.com

Port (only if non‑standard): :8080

Context path (often version): /v1

Resource path: /customers

Environment handling in automation:
Different environments (dev, qa, staging, prod) have different base URLs.

Never hardcode endpoints in tests - use property files or environment variables.

Example with Maven profiles:
properties

# qa.properties api.base.url=https://qa-api.example.com # prod.properties api.base.url=https://api.example.com

Interview question:
"How do you manage different endpoint environments in your automation framework?"
Expected answer: We externalize configuration using property files (one per environment) and select the active environment via a system property or Maven profile. The test code reads api.base.url from the active configuration, never hardcoding it.

---

Part 2: REST API Deep Dive (Table‑Free)

The Six REST Constraints (Must Memorize)

Client‑Server separation - The user interface is independent from data storage.

Stateless - Each request from client to server must contain all necessary information; the server never stores client context between requests.

Cacheable - Responses must define themselves as cacheable or not; clients can reuse cached responses.

Layered system - The client cannot tell whether it is communicating directly with the end server or an intermediate layer (load balancer, gateway).

Uniform interface - All resources are identified using a consistent naming scheme and manipulated using standard HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE).

Code‑on‑demand (optional) - Servers can send executable code (e.g., JavaScript) to extend client functionality.

---

HTTP Methods - Complete Reference (No Table)

GET - Read only
Corresponds to CRUD: Read

Idempotent? Yes - multiple identical requests produce the same result

Safe? Yes - does not change resource state

Request body allowed? No (body is ignored)

Response should contain the requested resource representation

POST - Create or submit
Corresponds to CRUD: Create

Idempotent? No - each POST may create a new resource with a different identifier

Safe? No - it changes server state

Request body allowed? Yes - contains data for the new resource

Response should contain a location header (URL of created resource) and/or the created resource

PUT - Replace (full update)
Corresponds to CRUD: Update (replace entire resource)

Idempotent? Yes - sending the same PUT request multiple times leaves the same result

Safe? No

Request body allowed? Yes - contains the complete updated resource

Response often returns the updated resource or just a status (200 or 204)

PATCH - Partial update
Corresponds to CRUD: Update (modify only specific fields)

Idempotent? Not guaranteed by HTTP spec - depends on implementation

Safe? No

Request body allowed? Yes - contains only the fields to change

Response similar to PUT

DELETE - Remove
Corresponds to CRUD: Delete

Idempotent? Yes - after deletion, subsequent DELETE requests return the same result (resource gone)

Safe? No

Request body allowed? Usually no

Response often returns 204 No Content

Important definitions:
Idempotent - Making the same request multiple times has the same effect as making it once.

Safe - The method does not modify any resource on the server (read‑only).

Real‑project examples:
GET /users/123 – retrieve user data (safe, idempotent)

POST /orders – create a new order (not idempotent – creates a new order each time)

PUT /users/123 – completely replace user 123's data (idempotent)

PATCH /users/123 – change only the email address (may be idempotent if implemented correctly)

DELETE /orders/456 – delete order 456 (idempotent)

Common mistake:
Using a GET request to update data. This violates the HTTP specification and can cause caching issues. For example:
Wrong: GET /user/update?name=John

Correct: PUT /user/123 with body {"name":"John"}

Interview question:
"Can you make a POST request idempotent?"
Answer: The HTTP specification does not require POST to be idempotent, but you can implement idempotency on the server side using client‑generated idempotency keys. For example, Stripe's API accepts an Idempotency-Key header so that duplicate POST requests do not create duplicate charges.

---

Anatomy of a REST API Request

A complete HTTP request for a REST API looks like this:
text
POST /v1/users/123/orders?status=active&page=2 HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
Content-Type: application/json
Authorization: Bearer eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIs...
Accept: application/json
Content-Length: 247
{
  "productId": "P100",
  "quantity": 2,
  "shippingAddress": "123 Main St"
}

Breakdown of components:
HTTP Method - POST (the action to perform)

Path parameters - /users/123/orders – the 123 is a path parameter identifying which user

Query parameters - ?status=active&page=2 – optional filtering, sorting, or pagination data

Headers - metadata about the request:

Host – target server

Content-Type – format of the request body (JSON, XML, etc.)

Authorization – credentials or token

Accept – desired response format

Body (payload) - actual data sent with POST, PUT, or PATCH (not with GET/DELETE)

---

Path Parameters vs Query Parameters - Clear Distinction

Path parameters:
Are part of the URL path - they identify a specific resource

Usually required (the request would be incomplete without them)

Example: /customers/{customerId} – here {customerId} is a path parameter

Another example: /orders/{orderId}/items/{itemId} – two path parameters

Query parameters:
Appear after the ? symbol in the URL

Are optional and used for filtering, sorting, or pagination

Example: /orders?status=shipped&limit=20&offset=0

Multiple query parameters are separated by &

How to tell them apart in a URL:
https://api.example.com/v1/users/789/orders?status=delivered
789 is a path parameter (comes after /users/)

status=delivered is a query parameter (after ?)

Real project examples:
GET /employees/E1001 – E1001 is path parameter

GET /employees/E1001/addresses – E1001 is path parameter

GET /products?category=laptops&minPrice=500 – both are query parameters

GET /reports/2024/sales?quarter=Q1 – 2024 is path parameter, quarter=Q1 is query parameter

Code example using Rest Assured:
java
// Path parameter
given()
    .pathParam("userId", "789")
.when()
    .get("/users/{userId}/orders")
    
// Query parameter
given()
    .queryParam("status", "delivered")
    .queryParam("page", 2)
.when()
    .get("/orders")

---

Headers vs Body

Headers (metadata) - typical examples:
Content-Type: application/json – tells the server what format the body uses

Accept: application/json – tells the server what format the client wants back

Authorization: Bearer <token> – carries authentication information

User-Agent: MyApp/1.0 – identifies the client software

Cookie: sessionId=abc123 – sends session cookie (less common in REST APIs)

Body (payload) - actual business data:
Present only in POST, PUT, and PATCH requests (not in GET or DELETE)

Format is usually JSON, but can be XML, form data, or plain text

Contains fields like name, address, price, quantity, etc.

Example of a request body (JSON):
json
{
  "firstName": "John",
  "lastName": "Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "age": 30
}

Sending files:
To upload a file, you must use multipart/form-data content type

The file is sent as part of the body, but with a special boundary marker

In Rest Assured: .multiPart("file", new File("document.pdf"))

---

Part 3: JSON and JsonPath for Testers (No Tables)

JSON Basics - Structure and Types

JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a lightweight data format consisting of key‑value pairs.
Allowed data types:
String - "name": "Alice"

Number - "age": 30 or "price": 19.99

Boolean - "active": true

Null - "middleName": null

Array - "tags": ["api", "testing", "automation"]

Object (nested) - "address": {"street": "123 Main", "city": "Boston"}

Real API response example:
json
{
  "status": "SUCCESS",
  "code": 200,
  "data": {
    "userId": 1001,
    "userName": "johndoe",
    "email": "john@example.com",
    "roles": ["admin", "viewer"],
    "profile": {
      "firstName": "John",
      "lastName": "Doe",
      "age": 28,
      "address": {
        "street": "456 Park Ave",
        "city": "New York",
        "zip": "10001"
      }
    }
  },
  "timestamp": "2025-06-14T10:30:00Z"
}

---

JsonPath Syntax - How to Extract Data

JsonPath is like XPath for JSON. It lets you navigate and extract parts of a JSON document.
Core operators:
$ – root element (starting point)

. – child operator (go one level down)

.. – recursive descent (search anywhere below)

* – wildcard (all elements)

[n] – array index (zero‑based)

[start:end] – array slice

?(@.condition) – filter predicate

Examples using the JSON above:
To get the status: $.status → "SUCCESS"

To get the user ID: $.data.userId → 1001

To get the first role: $.data.roles[0] → "admin"

To get all roles: $.data.roles[*] → ["admin","viewer"]

To get the first name: $.data.profile.firstName → "John"

To get the city: $.data.profile.address.city → "New York"

To find all user names where email contains example.com: $.data[?(@.email contains 'example.com')].userName

Working with arrays of objects:
json
{
  "courses": [
    {"id": 1, "name": "Java", "price": 299},
    {"id": 2, "name": "Python", "price": 199},
    {"id": 3, "name": "API Testing", "price": 399}
  ]
}

JsonPath examples for this structure:
First course name: $.courses[0].name → "Java"

Last course name: $.courses[-1].name → "API Testing"

All courses with price > 200: $.courses[?(@.price > 200)]

Names of courses with price < 300: $.courses[?(@.price < 300)].name

Code example - extracting values in Rest Assured:
java
import io.restassured.path.json.JsonPath;
String response = given()
    .when()
    .get("/users/1001")
    .asString();
JsonPath js = new JsonPath(response);
String userName = js.getString("data.userName");
int userId = js.getInt("data.userId");
List<String> roles = js.getList("data.roles");
String firstRole = js.getString("data.roles[0]");
String city = js.getString("data.profile.address.city");

---

Serialization and Deserialization (Important for Interviews)

Definitions:
Serialization = Converting a Java object into a JSON string (used when sending a request body)

Deserialization = Converting a JSON string into a Java object (used when parsing a response)

Why we use POJOs (Plain Old Java Objects):
Type safety - the compiler catches field name or type mismatches

Cleaner code - no string concatenation to build JSON

Easy maintenance - change the POJO once, and all tests that use it are updated

IDE support - autocomplete, refactoring, and navigation

Example - Request POJO:
java
public class CreateUserRequest {
    private String name;
    private String email;
    private int age;
    private List<String> roles;
    private Address address;
    
    // constructors, getters, setters
}
public class Address {
    private String street;
    private String city;
    private String zipCode;
    // getters/setters
}

Serialization - Java object to JSON (automatic in Rest Assured):
java
CreateUserRequest request = new CreateUserRequest();
request.setName("John Doe");
request.setEmail("john@example.com");
