HTTP Status Codes - Quick Reference (Grouped by Category)

2xx - Success
200 OK - Everything worked (standard success)

201 Created - A new resource was successfully created (usually after POST)

202 Accepted - Request accepted but processing is not finished (asynchronous)

204 No Content - Success but the response has no body (common for DELETE)

3xx - Redirection
301 Moved Permanently - Resource has a new permanent URL

304 Not Modified - Cached version is still valid (used with conditional GET)

4xx - Client Errors (the tester's best friends)
400 Bad Request - The request is malformed or contains invalid parameters

401 Unauthorized - Authentication is required or failed (not logged in)

403 Forbidden - Authenticated but does not have permission to access the resource

404 Not Found - The requested resource does not exist

405 Method Not Allowed - Using the wrong HTTP verb (e.g., POST on a read‑only endpoint)

409 Conflict - Request conflicts with the current state (e.g., duplicate entry)

422 Unprocessable Entity - Validation errors (semantically wrong, e.g., invalid email format)

429 Too Many Requests - Rate limit exceeded

5xx - Server Errors (should be treated as bugs)
500 Internal Server Error - The server encountered an unexpected condition

502 Bad Gateway - The server received an invalid response from an upstream server

503 Service Unavailable - The server is overloaded or down for maintenance

504 Gateway Timeout - The upstream server did not respond in time

Interview question:
"Explain the difference between 401 and 403 in simple terms."
Answer:
401 means "Who are you?" - authentication failed (missing or invalid credentials).

403 means "I know who you are, but you are not allowed to do this" - authentication succeeded but authorization failed.

Scenario question:
"An API always returns 200 with an error message in the body when validation fails. Is that acceptable?"
Expected answer: No. HTTP status codes exist to indicate the category of the result. For validation errors, the API should return 400 or 422. Returning 200 with an error in the body breaks the uniform interface and makes monitoring and caching unreliable.

