Part 7: SoapUI for SOAP Web Services (Key Concepts)

Property Transfer - Chaining Requests

What it is: Taking a value from one response and injecting it into a subsequent request.
Real project scenario:
Call POST /createUser – response contains a userId

Call GET /users/{userId} – need to use that userId in the path

Call PUT /users/{userId} – again need the same userId

How to do it in SoapUI:
Use a Property Transfer test step.

Source: previous response, XPath expression //userId

Target: next request, path parameter userId

Alternative using Groovy script:
groovy
def response = context.expand('${CreateUserResponse#Response}')
def json = new JsonSlurper().parseText(response)
def userId = json.userId
testRunner.testCase.setPropertyValue("userId", userId.toString())

Then in the next request: http://server/users/${#TestCase#userId}

---

SoapUI Variables - Scope Levels

Project level - available to all test cases and test suites in the project

Test Suite level - shared only within that test suite

Test Case level - shared only within that test case

Global level - across all projects (defined in preferences)

Accessing variables:
In GUI: ${#Project#varName} or ${#TestCase#varName}

In Groovy script:
groovy

// set testRunner.testCase.setPropertyValue("key", "value") // get def val = context.expand('${#TestCase#key}')

---

Mocking in SoapUI (When Real Service Is Unavailable)

When to mock:
The real service is not yet developed (you are testing earlier than the backend team)

The real service is a third‑party API that charges per call or has strict rate limits

You need to simulate error responses (500, timeout, malformed data) that are hard to provoke in the real service

How to create a mock:
Import the WSDL into SoapUI

Right‑click → Generate Mock Service

Define mock responses (success, failure, empty)

Configure dispatch style (XPATH, QUERY_MATCH, SCRIPT)

Start the mock service on a local port (e.g., http://localhost:8080/mock)

Example - XPATH dispatch:
If request contains <amount>10000</amount>, return an approval response; otherwise return a standard response.
Interview question:
"What is the difference between mocking and stubbing?"
Answer:
Stubbing provides predefined responses to specific requests.

Mocking also verifies that the expected calls were made with the correct parameters. SoapUI primarily does stubbing; tools like Mockito (for Java unit tests) do full mocking. In API testing, the term "mocking" is often used loosely to mean stubbing.

