Part 9: Common Mistakes and Troubleshooting

Frequent Automation Mistakes

Mistake 1 - Hardcoding URLs and credentials
❌ Wrong: String url = "https://dev-api.company.com/users"

✅ Correct: Read from configuration: @Value("${api.base.url}") private String baseUrl;

Mistake 2 - Checking only the status code
❌ Wrong: only .then().statusCode(200)

✅ Correct: also validate response body, headers, and structure.

Mistake 3 - Not testing negative scenarios
Always include tests for: invalid input (400), missing auth (401), wrong permissions (403), non‑existent resource (404), wrong method (405).

Mistake 4 - Creating test dependencies (test ordering)
❌ Wrong: Test A creates a user, Test B assumes that user exists.

✅ Correct: Each test creates its own data and cleans it up afterwards.

Mistake 5 - No retry logic for flaky APIs (eventual consistency)
Use TestNG's retryAnalyzer or a simple loop with delay.

Mistake 6 - Not cleaning up test data
Always delete created resources in @AfterMethod or @AfterClass to avoid polluting the environment.

---

Troubleshooting Common Issues

Issue 1 - Connection refused
Possible causes: service not running, wrong port, firewall blocking.

Fix: Check service health endpoint, verify URL, test with curl or Postman.

Issue 2 - SSL handshake error (self‑signed certificates)
Quick fix for testing only (never use in production):
java

given().relaxedHTTPSValidation().get("https://self-signed.badssl.com");

Issue 3 - SocketTimeoutException
The server is too slow or the timeout is too short.

Increase timeout in Rest Assured:
java

given() .config(RestAssured.config() .httpClient(HttpClientConfig.httpClientConfig() .setParam("http.socket.timeout", 10000)))

Issue 4 - JSON parsing exception
The response might be HTML (error page) instead of JSON.

Workaround: log the raw response before parsing.

Issue 5–401 (Unauthorized) in the middle of a test suite
Token expired. Implement token refresh (see TokenManager earlier).

