Part 10: Interview Questions - Quick Prep

Conceptual Questions

Q: Explain your API automation framework architecture.
A: We use Rest Assured + TestNG + Maven + ExtentReports + Log4j2. The framework is layered: configuration layer (property files), client layer (wrappers around Rest Assured), POJO layer (request/response models), test data layer (JSON files/factories), and test layer (TestNG classes). We also have a token manager and environment switcher. Jenkins runs smoke tests on every commit and regression nightly.

Q: How do you handle dynamic values (timestamps, random IDs)?
A: We generate them at runtime using java.util.UUID or System.currentTimeMillis() and store them in test case variables. For values that must be consistent across multiple requests, we extract from the first response using JsonPath and reuse.

Q: What is your process for testing an undocumented API?
A: I use browser developer tools to capture network requests while using the web application. Then I import those requests into Postman or Rest Assured. I also ask the developers for OpenAPI/Swagger documentation or look at the client‑side code to infer expected payloads.

Q: How do you test rate limiting?
A: I write a test that sends many requests in a loop (using multi‑threading) and checks that after a certain threshold the API returns 429 Too Many Requests. I also verify the Retry-After header and test that after waiting, the limit resets.

Scenario‑Based Questions

Scenario 1: API returns correct data but sometimes takes 10 seconds. What do you do?
A: I log a performance bug with the SLA. I add a timeout assertion in my tests (e.g., .time(lessThan(2000L))) so that violations are caught. I work with the dev team to profile the endpoint – it could be a slow database query, an external call, or lack of caching. I also suggest implementing async processing if the operation is inherently long.

Scenario 2: Test passes locally but fails on Jenkins. Where do you look?
A: I check:

Environment differences (URLs, test data, configuration)

Network latency (timeouts too aggressive)

Authentication token freshness (Jenkins may have an older token)

Parallel execution interference (tests modifying shared data)

Java / library version mismatches

Scenario 3: A third‑party API you depend on is down. How do you continue testing?
A: I mock the third‑party API using WireMock or SoapUI. I record real responses and replay them. This allows my tests to run without the external dependency. I also separate integration tests (against real service) from component tests (against mocks) so that only a subset is blocked.

Scenario 4: The API team changed the response structure, breaking all your tests. How do you minimize this risk in the future?
A: We implement contract testing using JSON Schema validation in every build. When the schema changes, the test fails early. We also use versioned APIs (/v1/, /v2/) so that old clients continue to work. We encourage the API team to use consumer‑driven contracts (e.g., Pact) so that changes are negotiated before they break consumers.

