Comprehensive Notes: SOAP API Testing & Automation - From Manual to Scripted Validation-Draft1
Overview and Purpose
These notes are written from an Automation Tester / SDET perspective for both real‑world project implementation and interview preparation. The material covers SOAP web service testing using tools like SoapUI (referred to in the source as "Soap Way") with a Google Maps API demo project. All explanations are original, restructured, and enhanced to reflect current industry best practices.
Topics include: importing sample projects, managing API keys, property scoping (project, test case, context), extracting values from XML responses using XPath, handling XML namespaces, transferring properties between requests, scripting with Groovy, and validating responses.

---

1. SOAP Web Services - Foundation for Testers
1.1 What is SOAP?
SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol) is an XML‑based messaging protocol for structured data exchange over web services.

It uses WSDL (Web Services Description Language) to define operations, request/response structures, and endpoints.

Common transport protocol: HTTP/HTTPS (also SMTP, TCP).

Message structure: Envelope (mandatory) → Header (optional) → Body (mandatory) → Fault (optional error element).

1.2 Why SOAP Testing Matters for Automation Testers
SOAP services remain widely used in enterprise integrations (banking, telecom, government).

Testing requires understanding of XML, namespaces, XPath, and WS‑Security.

Typical tools: SoapUI, Postman (with limitations), or custom Java code (JAX‑WS, SAAJ).

Key challenges: handling namespaces, extracting dynamic values (session IDs, timestamps), and chaining requests.

1.3 SOAP vs REST - Quick Comparison (No Table)
Protocol and style
SOAP: strict, XML‑based protocol.

REST: architectural style, supports JSON/XML/plain text.

State management
SOAP: can be stateful (using WS‑Session).

REST: stateless by design.

Security
SOAP: built‑in WS‑Security.

