5. Property Scopes and Variable Management
5.1 Levels of Properties (No Table - Bulleted List)
Global - syntax: #Global#propertyName. Lifetime: across all projects. Use for: environment URLs, shared credentials.

Project - syntax: #Project#propertyName. Lifetime: within the project. Use for: API keys, base endpoints.

TestSuite - syntax: #TestSuite#propertyName. Lifetime: within the suite. Use for: data shared across test cases in a suite.

TestCase - syntax: #TestCase#propertyName. Lifetime: within the test case. Use for: request‑specific data.

Context - syntax: #Context#propertyName. Lifetime: during test run (scripts only). Use for: temporary variables in Groovy.

System - syntax: #System#propertyName. Lifetime: JVM system properties. Use for: rarely used, generally avoid.

5.2 Property Expansion in SOAP Requests
Inside a request XML, write: ${#Project#apiKey}. The tool replaces this with the actual value at runtime.
5.3 Context vs Message Exchange in Scripts
context object – holds properties accessible during test case execution. You can read/write using context.setProperty("key", value) and context.getProperty("key").

messageExchange object – represents the actual request/response. Used to access raw HTTP details, attachments, etc.

testRunner object – controls test execution (e.g., testRunner.fail("reason")).

Example: Extracting a value using messageExchange
groovy
def response = messageExchange.response.responseContent
def xml = new XmlSlurper().parseText(response)
xml.declareNamespace('ns':'http://example.com')
def extractedId = xml.'ns:Response'.'ns:Id'.text()
context.setProperty('dynamicId', extractedId)

Common mistake: Trying to access properties defined at test case level from a script without using context.getProperty. Always use context or testRunner methods.

