8. Handling Namespaces - Detailed Strategy
8.1 Why Namespaces Break XPath
Consider this response:
xml
<soap:Envelope xmlns:soap="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/">
  <soap:Body>
    <tns:GetAddressResponse xmlns:tns="http://maps.example.com/">
      <tns:Address>...</tns:Address>
    </tns:GetAddressResponse>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>

XPath //Address returns nothing because the node is actually tns:Address.
8.2 Three Ways to Handle Namespaces in SOAP Testing
Ignore namespaces with a wildcard (quick but risky):
//*:Address selects any element with local name "Address" regardless of namespace.
Risk: if multiple namespaces have the same local name, results are unpredictable.

Declare the namespace in the tool:
In SoapUI's XPath dialog: click "Declare Namespace" → prefix ns1 → URI http://maps.example.com/
Then use: //ns1:Address.

Use the local-name() function:
//*[local-name()='Address'] – works but is verbose.

8.3 Scripting Approach - Registering a Namespace in Java
java
import javax.xml.xpath.*;
import org.xml.sax.InputSource;
// ... inside your test
XPathFactory factory = XPathFactory.newInstance();
XPath xpath = factory.newXPath();
xpath.setNamespaceContext(new NamespaceContext() {
    public String getNamespaceURI(String prefix) {
        return prefix.equals("tns") ? "http://maps.example.com/" : null;
    }
    // other methods can return null for brevity
});
String address = xpath.evaluate("//tns:Address/text()", new InputSource(new StringReader(response)));

Interview question: How do you handle dynamic namespaces that change per environment?
Answer: Extract the namespace URI from the response using regex or XML parsing, then register it dynamically. Alternatively, use XPath with local-name().

